76561198106292207,Recommended,272270,32396046,Posted: 13 June,all,eijolend,"TL;DR:An excellent game. Don't get this if you're just looking for tactical combat game. However, if you want a story heavy game or are even tangentially interested in the Numenera setting, definitely check this one out!--Game Mechanics--Let me start this by saying that I bought this game because I'm a big fan of the Numenera Tabletop RPG. I was a bit worried how the system would translate to a computer game and was pleasantly surprised how well it worked out. Some parts were adapted to better fit the new format, but the core features are all there and the game does a good job using the resolution mechanic.The combat system is up to standards, but nothing to write home about. Tactical combat is definitely not the focus of this game.--Story and Setting--I found the main story quite enjoyable, which doesn't really pick up pace until after you finished the first third of the game. It explores some interesting concepts and even though it is a bit heavy handed at times, I found the end very intriguing. However, I feel the game is at least as much - if not more so - about painting a picture of this weird setting. While most of the sidequests and dialog options are not relevant for the main story, they show you a glimpse of this extraordinary world that you find yourself in. In my opinion, this is the part the game excels at - portraying a colorful and weird, but interesting world.I'm also very happy that the way this game presents the setting fits right in with the rest of the Numenera universe and I would say it is a good starting point for anyone interested in the Ninth World.--Misc--I finished my first playthrough in about 28 hours. I did most side quests, but ignored some that didn't interest me and I'm sure there are a few I simply haven't found. There were multiple points where I still wonder what would have happened if I handled things differently - especially with the stories of the companions I picked. I immediately felt inspired to start another game with a character that has a rather different outlook on life and a different choice of party members."
76561198114807114,Not Recommended,272270,31187803,Posted: 16 April,all,Mat,"I don't do speed runs, I don't ignore side quests yet the first run through took only thirteen hours to complete this game. (I have no wish for a 2nd run through)  I'd like to say this was down to my brilliant RPG skills cutting through the Gordian Knot but given it took me 23 hours to complete Tyranny (not known for it's length); no, this game is short and I'm feeling short changed.I'd make some combat about how weak the combat system was, but I really didn't see enough of it to be qualified to comment.  I think I had a grand total of 5 fights (or crisis) all game, what little I saw did not impress me.  In most RPG's you see more fights before getting out of the tutorial.  All that really sticks in my mind was how slow it was, if there was an option to speed up the enemy animation I didn't find it, those few fights I did have really dragged.Without combat, what was there?  Puzzles?  What was there was so simple I'm not sure they were meant to be a puzzle or not.  The game was mostly running back and forth, clicking on NPC's and ploughing through the turgid dialogue.  I think the writers used every word in the dictionary except brevity, very little of it was useful to completing the plot.  At no point did I need to engage my brain in this game.  Humour?  Nope.  I got more laughs from watching Clockwork Orange.The real killer though wasn't it only took 13 hours to complete.  No, the clincher is; at no point in those 13 hours do I remember enjoying the game."
76561197996685344,Recommended,272270,25429618,"Posted: 9 September, 2016",all,kriton,"As a 33 year old lawyer I consider myself somewhat of a ""stealth gamer"". It took my girlfriend 9 months to find out that I like video games... Due to a busy work schedule my Steam time is somewhat limited so I normally don't squander it writing reviews. But for this game I will make an exception.I was not familiar with the Numenera universe before playing the early access version of this game. (I still don't feel ""familiar"" after completing the early access version.) I consider myself a diehard planescape fan and couldn't suppress the feeling that the developers simply couldn't afford or wouldn't dish out the necessary funds to use the the planescape universe and make a ""real successor"" to Plancescape Torment.Boy, was I wrong!After playing this for 22.5 hours it went from my ""I'll look into it"" pile to my ""dear god, no more delays"" pile.The writing is simply stellar. The characters have incredible depth. The themes are mature and compelling. The developers have avoided the infamous genre pitfalls and clichés (""avenge loved ones, rescue princess, save the world""). Tides of Numenara is without a doubt the most original rpg I have ever played.I hope that the decision to make the game available across many different platforms will make it more available to audiences, who have avoided the rpg genre due to the above-mentioned clichés. In my view, this title shows that great art comes in many forms - even in the form of a video game.If you truly enjoyed Planescape Torment this is for you."
,Not Recommended,272270,30446586,Posted: 11 March,all,existential_vacuum,"Planescape: Torment, arguably the best RPG ever made. The game with cult following and, when it comes to story, nearly no contenders out there.A new challenger appears -Torment: Tides of Numenera, the game from the people behind PS:T. Will it prove that the heights of PS:T can be reached, that people still can make games with unique setting and strong personal story? Will it be a spiritual successor to highly aclaimed RPG?Plot twist, it won't and here is why (in the form of the glorious WALL OF TEXT).Spoiler-free tl:dr version at the end.WritingWhat can change the writing of the game?Main PlotThe main plot revolves around The Last Castoff or better to say it doesn't. It revolves around the Resonance Chamber, a macguffin to fix it all, stop the menacing Sorrow and save all the Castoffs. The premise drops to much information (in the form of walls of text upon walls of text) and the game for the next 5-10 hours has nothing to add to the plot, aside from go there he/she knows. Everything from there on adds to the exposition of the weird things in the world. World building is important, yes, but it is essential to establish rules of the world and in T:ToN there are none. Psyonics. Timetravel. Constructs. Nanomachines. All of it is just there for the sake of being and all of it is presented , you can guess, through walls of text.After 10 hours of reading I asked myself, what was it I was supposed to do? The game presents no urgency, there is no menace. It contradicts what it tells you in the beginning. Then, there is a plot twist, which should have shifted the focus from Resonance Chamber and feel the urgency to act fast, but it doesn't. It is simply presented and the player suddenly has to care about it. And after 10 more hours there is another plot twist and more exposition as to provide the motivation of the villain (finally).The ending is presented in a style of Mass Effect 3: you did a lot of stuff throughout the game but it doesn't matter, choose an option. And it ends.CompanionsPS:T had a wide range of non-typical companions with unique personalities and ties to the protagonist in one way or another. A talking skull, tiefling, githzerai, a piece of armor and it is without saying anything about their personalities. Just the appearance.T:ToN has humans. All of them. And that tells you something from the very beginning. Their stories are bland, their unique quests are just ""carry me around and at a certain point I'll tell you something"" and that's basicaly it. Their arcs (if you can call their stories that) end abruptly and give no satisfaction.Writing itselfThe game has been advertised having word count higher than the Bible and that's not an exageration. Word count is too damn high. Everything in T:ToN drops a wall of text upon the player, for right and wrong reasons. The game lacks editors hand, who would have cut half of the text.Such word count would be okay if it delivered something superb, unique and interesting. Instead, it spills nonsense and amateurish purple prose.It does get better by the second half of the game, because the amount of text is significantly reduced, but by that time, you will be tired of it all.GameplayI may be bested in battle, but I shall never be waiting for 10 minutes for enemy's turn to endSkillchecks or Effort systemIn T:ToN attributes (Might, Speed, Intelegence) are presented in forms of pools. Each pool can be used to increase the chance to succeed in skillcheck (either in combat or dialogue). The player can replenish the pool by resting or using special items.Starts as an interesting mechanic and ends as a easy way to bypass and win at everything. Companion pool in 50% of events can be used in checks, items to replenish pools are everywhere making skillchecks a joke.CombatDevelopers wanted to improve the combat as opposed to PS:T. They failed.The combat is bad as in worse than in 99. Enemy turns take forever (literaly as AI can simply freeze and do nothing forcing to reload). There wouldn't be any problem if combat, as it was stated, was really optional. It is not. There are forced situations, which can be finished without killing anyone, but are nonetheless buggy and force to reload time and time again.Character classesThere are 3 classes and the only one you have to consider is Nano (aka Mage). Why? Because 60% of skillchecks are Intelegence bassed. Going with anything else results in failing checks and combat. And why combat is bad? Check above.ArtdirectionOur progenitor was funny like that. Substance for the next location was always a last minute decision.LocationsLet's go location after location.Sagus Cliffs- a place where everything is an attraction. Here you see a strange looking clock, there you see a strange generator, here a strange fountain with fish-like creatures instead of water, there a soundproof building and a place of diplomacy. It is so obsessed with little things that it fails as a whole.Valley of the Dead Heroes- a place of backer content. Though the most generic location, it has the most interesting quest - Endless Gate (which appears out of nowhere, sadly).Bloom- the only location in the game that feels consistent in what it is. The art is solid and supports the narative.Oasis- nothing to say about it, 'cause it has been cut.Calm- there's not much of it but it looks okay primary because of the fanthoms.Overall, in comparison to Pillars of Eternity, locations feel cheep and lowres.UIIt is atrocious. The inventory has no sorting. Trade screen has no appropriate buttons and has ""it's not a bug but a feature"" feel. Dialogue interface takes a lot of screen space but only 50% of it is text box. CYOA sequences have no proper scaling of elements and thus look like an indie project with low budget.All in all, as one man said, it looks like a Winamp skin.PortraitsJust plain bad. They had great portraits in alpha-beta build and changed them to low effort paint over photo. Moreover, none of the NPCs have portraits, though in alpha they were there.Bonus section. inXile's communication or lack of thereofIt was mentioned time and time again - cut content, which was promised during kickstarter campaign. It isn't the problem something was cut, such is the nature of game development, the problem is it wasn't properly mentioned until the exposure.Right now inXile is somewhat ignorant of the complaints regarding the final product. Technical forum is filled with unanswered threads and I gave up refreshing the page to see if the problems I mentioned are going to be addressed.tl:drProsthe design and pacing of The Bloom hub;multiple quests resolutions (sometimes more than 3);several interesting sidequests.Consbad and buggy combat system;bland companions;weird world for the sake of weirdness with little to no explanation, why and how everything works;mediocre main plot, which goes from ""personal story"" to ""chosen one story"";choices don't matter;abrupt ending akin to Mass Effect 3;atrocious consolidized UI without proper scaling;cut kickstarter strechgoals;VerdictA lot more can be said about each aspect of the game, but there isn't enough space.The game as a spiritual successor toPlanescape: Tormentgets a solid 2 out of 10 for failing to do everything it was destined to do: improve combat, tell a complex personal story, have unique companions and present reactivity, choice and real consequences.PS:T aside, it gets 5 out of 10 for trying to be original but failing to do everything else properly."
,Not Recommended,272270,30248028,Posted: 28 February,all,RafUnforgiven,"Pros:- Mechanics: Game works very well mechanically, including options to interact with terrain is a certain feature I've craved for in isometric RPG's- Story and setting: Story and dialogue are very decent, characters seem memorable and interesting.Cons:- Cut Content: I don't thik I've ever seen a case, more brutal than this one. When the game was in early Alpha, it contained several additional features that are unavaible now at release, some being key to incorporating the true feeling of playing in the Numenera universe. The intro sequence and start was severely reduced and it doesn't seem that that content shows up later on, it's just... gone. 3 out of the 9 promised companions were also cut with the argument they want to focus their efforts on developing a deeper evolution for fewer characters than spreading their efforts out.Now the last and most dissappointing fact that was falsely hyped up (some would say promised) by the developers: only 3 foci... The essence and meat of the tabletop rpg Numenera is the plethora of foci you can choose from at character creation and the amount of starting diversity that offers you. When the alpha/beta started, one could only choose between 3 such foci, each one more or less designated to work with a certain type, so you can get a feel for the game. Back then, there was even a message that popped up as you were choosing, stating there will be more options in the full game.Well those promised additional options never made it in the full game for some reason and what's most annoying about this situation is that these issues were either never adressed or flimsy minor excuses were presented to justify these decisions.The only reason I could think of for all this content being cut/removed, is they want to add it as future DLC... Which 1st of all wouldn't work, because Isometric RPG's with a non-branching story don't go well with character options DLC, since most players will only play the game once. And 2ndly, the developers know they can't add cut content that was actually in the game at some point during the development as DLC, they probably know they'd get eaten alive for such silly and anti-consumer practices.Because of these confusing and silly decisions, I simply can't recommend the game to anyone.TL DR: Game is good, but lots of content was either cut for no logical reason, or never delivered despite being promised. Those cuts really hurt the game and don't give the Descriptor/Type/Focus system justice."
,Not Recommended,272270,30331406,Posted: 4 March,all,seanhogge,"Having now completed what must be about 80% of the story, it seems like my initial concerns were well-founded.In a nutshell, this is a very nice rough draft.Where to begin? Let's start with the choices. Most of the time, they feel inconsequential. Granted, characters die, NPCs can be killed or made friends, but never did I feel like the death of a party member (I lost one person) or letting Qorro live changed anything momentous.Skills and abilities didn't seem to matter much mostly because there are only about a dozen fights through the whole game. The advancement system seems very compelling, and I was excited to progress. But then I never got a chance to use my new talents.Balance seems off, too. Either I found myself overwhelmed with up to a dozen foes with twice my hit points, or I was just talking my way through everything. I like that enemies could be spoken to during a crisis, but that only happened twice, maybe three times. The worst part about being outnumbered wasn't the frustration of difficulty, but how slow and repetetive the battles got. I'm looking at you, corpuscular maws.Plus the game feels short, the pacing is tedious (if well-narrated), the voice acting is confusingly sporadic, crisis instructions were vague at best, and most of the game is the script to a cut scene that budget didn't allow to be rendered.It's got great ideas. It has a fun world and character advancement system. It just doesn't do anything with them that makes any of it exciting. Had I spent $15, I wouldn't complain (or replay). At $45, I have to warn others to wait for a discount or a better option from another developer."
76561198011231411,Recommended,272270,29374074,Posted: 20 January,all,Scoundrelus,"I'm not a professional reviewer or anything but I'm 32 (golden age of gaming) years old and I've played and finished every single CRPG on the planet, some of them multiple times.  This game definitely has the potential to be among the best I've played.  The writing it fantastic but I have to say, what I like the most is how the game mechanics are setup.  Most games like this you would reload if your character fails at doing something or persuading someone, but the way Torment is set up failure can lead to something new and interesting and the best moral choice won't always lead to the best moral outcome.  I love that because it simulates real life decision making.  Nothing is black and white.Post Release Edit:I've just finished the game.  I definitely feel like there's a lot of room for replay because of all the branching choices. I still stand by my original words but I do feel mildly disappointed though I feel it's my fault.  Torment isn't really an CRPG in the traditional sense.  I feel it's more of a point and click adventure game with some combat elements (mind you I was a Jack so I got through many things without combat).  I was very excited to hear that the game was set 1 billion years in the future. I am a fan of all things sci-fi.  I love the bizarre and unknown and some of the concepts in the game (such as the Bloom) were genuinely cool.However the downside is being so far out made it also somewhat unrelateable.  I had a hard time caring for any of my companions. I also believe I've been spoiled by voice acting in RPGs. I don't mind reading at all but I honestly prefer to read what an NPC said rather than a novel-like narration though the skill with which it was written has my respect.One let down was the lack of a world map.  I though perhaps I would get to visit some of these places I heard about in the game but alas they were only lore.  I was disappointed with the overall plot though there were some twists I didn't see coming. I felt like the billion year into the future plot was really interesting but I really wish it was more organized.  I felt like there were a lot of random elements and things that didn't really fit in well together. I also wish I could delve more into the backstories of some of the more interesting elements.  For example, I wanted to know a lot more about the Bloom than what was given.Overall, it's a good game though I believe Planescape Torment was better (though in all fairness I am a fan of that universe).  Perhaps it's just me since this is my first experience with Monte Cook, maybe if more comes out in this universe I'll grow to understand it better."
76561198027117855,Recommended,272270,20781342,"Posted: 26 January, 2016",all,Clint Eastwood,"Where to begin... I am an old school Planescape: Torment fan, and a D&D tabletop player/DM. Let's set a few things straight about this game:1) Best Writing Ever! Amazing story, characters and settings with personalities of their own.2) Uniquely awe-inspiring environments with unforgettable experiences around every corner.3) A massive project filled with love, both from the Devs and the Fans!4) The Spiritual Successor to Planescape: Torment, and I could not be any prouder!5) Just to clarify: This is not D&D, nor is it technically part of the D&D universe... but it's also technically could be, in a way. Afterall, Planescape: Torment took place in Sigil, and that city could take you anywhere in the universe... I wish not to debate meta/universe lines or copyrights, so I will just leave it as that. No it doesn't explicitly have any connection to the previous game, but the feel, wonderful bizarrities and incredible writing feel right at home.Thus far, the game has been amazing. It has the updated graphics and sounds (plus voice acting!) that were needed to drive the series forward. Planescape: Torment is held dear to the hearts of many, and this game shall not disappoint! 12/10 Can't wait for the full release!If only it weren't so late... I want to play FOREVER!P.S. The in game bug-reporting system is great! I need to make a torment account, but I will surely be giving useful information to help squash bugs before release. I have only had one bug at the beginning, one of my guys couldn't move during combat. I hit the space bar or something to skip the turn and it fixed it. Didn't cause a major issue."
,Not Recommended,272270,30327275,Posted: 4 March,all,Sapidianus,"You can't threaten or persuade a common kid into answering your questions. Either you pay him money or leave the dialogue.You can't get into a combat with a group of thugs competing with you for the same bounty, you have a gazzilion of dialogue options but you can't attack them and get into the real combat. Even if you manage to get one of them killed via one of the dialogue options you can't loot his corpse.Often you can't discuss a reward for a quest before you complete it. Even if the quest involves something illegal or risky you can't ask about your payment before you complete it.Often you have to believe when you are being lied too, because most of the time there is no option to claim that whatever obvious ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t a NPCs tells you is a lie.There is a lot of text, yes, but very few choices and ways to roleplay any other type of personality except a common good and nice hero, that helps every person in need them/she/he meets. For a game with focus on dialogues there are too few real options in dialogues besides asking questions."
76561198024270397,Not Recommended,272270,30295347,Posted: 3 March,all,Siollear,"I tried very hard to like this game, since Planescape:Torment was one of my favorite games growing up and I've been waiting 18 years for a new ""Torment"" game. But unfortunately, after about 30 hours, I have come to the conclusion that this is not a worthy successor. The characters are bland, the story is contrived, and some of the voice acting is so bad / irritating that I had to turn the voice-over volume to zero.The combat is a slog with basically no strategic curve, and the maps are hilariously cramped.You can easily tell that this game suffered from major budgetary constraints, technical limitations, and last minute cuts -- and that kind of ruins the immersion for me.This game is basically ""Wasteland 2"" with worse combat, UX, and maps. AND WL2 didnt really do any of those things particularly well to begin with."
,Not Recommended,272270,30278363,Posted: 2 March,all,Ookami,"So as the thumb shows. I don't recommend this and just to point this out. I did not back this on kickstarter and bought this purely on an ""looks like a neat RPG"" motive. I don't know Torment Planescape or have played it. I'm essentially new to this kind of ""world"" or... whatever it is people are comparing this to.So why do I not recommend Tides of Numenera?It's not a simple, short answer. I wish it was. It'd make it easier.Unlike other people who don't recommend this on the basis of ""can't create your character appearance"" I don't really mind it very much, but I will admit whoever drew the male and female 'main character' avatar pictures... should be fired. They're horrible, I've seen better ones in far worse games.It would have been nice if there was a place in-game where you could 'edit' your avatar's appearance (and that horrible picture), but like I said I don't find it too big of a problem. I pester npc's no matter my appearance. This is simply a QoL (Quality of Life) thing that 'would' have been nice to have, but does nothing to impact my opinion on the game as a whole.Now the 1st third of the game is in Sagus Cliffs is great. It's fun, it's interesting. Once you leave Sagus Cliff's to continue the story... it slowly, very slowly but surely gets worse.Adding onto the fact that if you do not have 3 companions with you after leaving Sagus, you're screwed as you'll never get another companion afterward. Why? No idea a ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ design decision I figure, and you CAN lose your companions so if you lose them, you don't get a replacement as you'll never return to the first city to grab another one, which in turn makes combat (if you get into it) annoyingly hard.EDIT: Thank to a few people who commented on my review. I've discovered you 'can' swap companions, but somehow in my playthrough I was never able to. Why? Apparently an item that allows you to swap them, was in all likelihood bugged for me and prevented this. Given you can't access the companions in later areas, it seems this bug I had with swapping them should have been dealt with 'before' release given it is particularly critical. (If albeit rare as I seem to be the lucky minority)And combat as it is in-game is like putting your hand in an active garbage disposal. Painful. Combat isn't fun, it isn't ""intuitive"" It's annoying, it's painful... it's tormenting. The game calls battles a ""crisis"" and it is one, for you because you're going to go through your own crisis trying to ""win"" these battles in a horribly made combat mechanic. So if you DO buy the game... avoid combat like you'd avoid getting the plague. You'll save yourself a lot of headaches.The 2nd part of the game (before getting to the end-game city) is strange, and not in the 'oh this is neat' strange. It's a ""What is this?"" kind of strange, with admittedly bits of the first kind. The 2nd part is mostly there so the dev's can say ""Hey, look at these names. They backed us."" Beyond that, it really serves no purpose in the game.The last part of the game is... almost as awesome as the first, but it wears off quickly and it gets replaced with annoyance. The third part of the game feels rushed, like some invisible force is whipping your character to do things right away and while you don't have to (and if you buy the game anyways) you should go slowly. Makes it a bit more enjoyable.But therein lies the problem. The first part of the game will take you 10 hours to get through it. The rest of the game... 8 hours and that is doing ""ALL"" of the side quests as well, exploring the cities, talking to npc's, etc.And it's not even worth replaying the game in a different way. It'll all lead down the same path no matter what. (Yay for youtube)Nothing changes very much beyond how much your companions ""like"" you, and how other npc's might, and it takes a lot to get them to dislike you. (All npc's generally dislike you to start with, so your screwed there either way)The companions, they aren't very... interesting. Actually no, I'm lying. Only 1 companion is interesting, and this is ""AFTER"" they cut 3 other companions to 'expand/flesh out' the six they kept. Apparently they didn't put much effort into five of these companions, so they probably should have just kept the other 3 anyways.The companion who is the most interesting (in my opinion) is Rhin. A girl misplaced in the world that you can save/adopt. Compared to all of the other companions who are interesting for a span of five minutes. Rhin is a companion you'll likely find far more interesting than half the maniacs who want to join you. However, she's a child and thus isn't made for combat which makes her even more interesting in my eyes. Eventually through the course of the game she eventually sees your character as a surrogate parent of sorts and then you'll come to a decision in the end part of the game... that just kicks you in the gut. This choice is: You can have her stay with you or return to her real family as you discover a way to send her home and if you (like me) really really like having her around. It's a painful choice to make.The rest don't have this kind of impact. The rest are screwed up beyond any measure of saving or bothering to learn about.Playing it, it feels like the dev's were doing good in the first part, but then said ""screw it"" and rushed up the rest just to shove it out the proverbial door and if the steam forums show anything.♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥off almost everyone who have backed the game because of cut content, changed goals, etc.Which even though I didn't back this. I feel it's a horrible move by the dev's given that while they have the choice. They should have brought it up to those who backed the game, the people who PAID them to create this game and paid for the ""cut content"" that isn't in the game. (Especially when people paid the 'stretch goals' for specific content and the dev's just told them it won't be there. (That's downright lying)Sure there are ""creative problems"" and issues they have to be worked through or past but they aren't allowed to make those kind of choices when the people who paid money for specific content are told ""Yeah, you paid for it to be in game but... we feel it's not a good choice to put it in. Sorry.""In business, this causes a business to go OUT of business as the investors abandon it for another business that'll do as it promises.Speaking of cut content... I'd say this decision was a bad move given how short the game is past the first part of the game, but chances are it was ""cut"" so it will be later added as paid dlc.If it doesn't I would be surprised.In the end, with the bad business practices, relatively short gameplay (with it's price as it is at the time of this review), no replayability, downright abusive combat mechanics, I can't recommend this game to anyone until it's priced around $20 (or regional equivelant)I'd give this game a 5 out of 10. It's average, in the end that's all it is. Instead of buying this, go watch a let's play on youtube. You'll find it more enjoyable and if combat happens. At least you won't be the one harmed by it."
