76561198002136110,Not Recommended,272270,31771281,Posted: 15 May,all,liverpooljohnny,"Like a lot of people here, I loved Planescape. The cRPGs - and especially the isometric RPGs new and old - are my favorite genre. I was so excited for this game, and I never would have expected that 6 hours in I would be so bored that I just couldn't go on.Others have written more detailed criticisms, but one I'd like to add: While critics applaud this game ""for its lack of combat"" because its ""refreshing"" and ""different"" what you get is a total lack of action.  I'm all for world building, character building, and exploration. But at some point, all you're doing is talking to one NPCs after another, each of whom have their own weird gimmick. Each one is trying so hard to be memorable and unique, but ultimately they all blend together. This is most likely because that's all there is to do. In my first 4 hours or so I literally encountered one combat situation (outside the tutorial). With nothing to break up the routine of walking and talking, I found myself not wanting to play.So I went back to Pillars of Eternity and started a new playthrough. Torment made me yearn for games that similar, but much better."
76561198051253452,Not Recommended,272270,30548954,Posted: 16 March,all,Eliosia,"I thought it was pretty cool at first. Very interesting and well-written. My only real complaint is that it's so short. I did absolutely every sidequest and stumbled into the ending in just over 30 hours. I was expecting the game (from the descriptions and adverts) to be at least longer than that. No real character development either. I mostly talked my way out of stuff, didn't have a name, couldn't customize my character. I mean, it's not a bad game to just try out, but for 45 dollars, I feel like I didn't get my money's worth. If you can catch it on sale, by all means give it a go, but I can't recommend it at its current price."
76561198026873914,Not Recommended,272270,30356524,Posted: 6 March,all,Ghouleh,"It's not very good.This has been one of the most anticipated Kickstarter games of all time, what with it's prestigious legacy, and it falls short.To be brief and fair, I'll not compare it to it's spiritual predecessor overmuch, and will instead judge it on it's own merits as it's own game.Torment: Tides of Numenera feels like a game that was in the oven for so long that it was held in stasis, while an entire generation of new, great cRPGs (the Divinities, Tyranny, Pillars of Eternity...) came and went. It's been in developement for four years, and yet it still feels like a rough draft that pales in comparison to what other luminaries of the genre accomplished with less.  It's on the short side for a cRPG, but I'll not hold it against Torment: I rather like shorter cRPGs, as Tyranny showed.The biggest problem I have with this game is how rough the interface and controls are. Movement is somewhat floaty and imprecise, interactable objects and characters can be tricky to click on, character icons can overlap and block environmental interactables, there is no fast movement/exploration option, the UI feels slow and clunky to resolve... It lacks polish is most every regard.One of the best ways to explain that lack of polish is in the sound design. There are many effects in the game without any accompanying sound effect, making for a weird feeling of incompleteness. The sound desgin that there -is- is actually quite bad, with many zones being hampered by repetitive, grating, loud and annoying sound effects. Coupled with the lackluster and sporadic voice-acting, after a while I just started playing without sound.Many people have complained that there is very little combat - and they're right. I can't remember participating in much more than a dozen combat encounters overall, but I won't chalk that up as a negative. One of the few innovations Torment brings to the table is the introduction of the Crisis System, a sort of turn-based gameplay that is mostly used for combat, but also for some interesting non-combat interactions, even in the -midst- of combat. Through the Crisis Sistem, you can interact with objects and other people even while in combat, which makes for an interesting, if not very refined experience.I had no problems at all with the very low number of combats throughout the game, especially because combat itself is not very enjoyable, what with that cardinal sin of 3D RPGs - slow and clunky animations.Torment utilizes Monte Cook's Numenera System and scenario. This is an entirely subjective point on my part, but I have never enjoyed Numenera, and this game has not changed my opinion. The mechanics of it are quite weird, and they exacerbate the particular mania of many a player.Specifically, especially in the lower levels (or 'Tiers'), you have to burn your attribute points in order to increase your chance to succeed at any particular task. Early on in game, you fail at most everything, missing all your attacks (I had a pitiable performance in the very first combat encounter in the game whereupon I missed all of my attacks for so many turns that combat ended, the boss literally taking pity on me and leaving) and must trade even your slightest chances to succeed later to have an ever slighter chance to succeed now. This curves rather awkardly - later on in the game once you've stacked enough Stats Pools and Edge, you steamroll through any and every test and check. There is not happy middle ground. In the end, it's pointless, because you can just savescum to succeed in most every check - and I'd argue that this system encourages you to.In addition, there are Cyphers, which are items that produce powerful, reliable effects - but are consumable, each Cypher having only one use, with very few exceptions.Having to burn your own Stat Pools to have a bigger chance to succeed, and almost all your powerful attacks being one-offs, feeds into that particular gamer paranoia of not wanting to use up your limited items or resources for the fear of needing them later. I know I'm not alone in this, and I finished the game whilst hardly using any Cyphers at all or burning Stat Pools beyond my Edge.Finally, there's the Numenera world itself - the Ninth World to be exact. It's a literal mishmash of random sci-fi and fantasy elements from dozens of different sources, what with the debris from different worlds and realities piling up in a giant junkyard reality, with nobody knowing anything about how anything works and just cobbling everything together from alien junk. The aesthetic is all over the place, from wooden shields to pilot jackets to H.R. Geiger walls to future guns. There is no consistent design, everything seems equally plausible, there are no real rules. It's hard to be invested in such a scatterbrained world.The story is- fine. Functional. The companions aren't bad, but they feel like holdovers from the Planescape Torment era. Nowadays we're used to much better written and relatable companions, from Obsidian to Bioware. It's just not good enough for the present age.In short, Torment: Tides of Numenera is a middling cRPG at best, unworthy of your hype, or your money. Avoid it unless on sale."
76561198052392096,Not Recommended,272270,30502978,Posted: 13 March,all,Chicken Attack Master,"Have you ever been offered chocolate cookies but after the first bite found it was raisins? Felt betrayed.""I am one with the tides, the tides is with me..."" - Castoff Chirrut Imwe - Admit it, they look alike.Expected more, but was disappointed.Encountered a great amount of bugs that made it dreadful. Battle mechanics was cheezy and does not pull you in. Some people say its not the main focus but should be more interesting.The story is rich and great but there should be a balance and events to get you back in.One thing I hated the most was the bugs on quests that shows complete but your journal never updates, then it freezes.It is so easy to avoid conflict. Once you have edge up you would never fail a task.Companions were interesting at first but then they get all over the place real quick as you go on and felt forced/rushed.The tides has a few impact on the game, unless you went Silver/Blue.It felt really incomplete. I hope in a year or so they implement all things they promised and more.Then I'll recommend it."
,Not Recommended,272270,30249981,Posted: 28 February,all,OldtimerZA,"EDIT: Review below.I am enjoying this game.BUT I have to give it a negative review because of the scummy business tactics used by inExile.No matter how good this game is , it is most certainly not a 5 year long , $5 million game.Where did the time and money go ? Other projects? Mismanagement?Who can truly say at this point.But the crux of the story is that this is NOT the game detailed and outlined on their kickstarter.(no where near it).It's ok to cut a few stretch goals to finish in the proposed time.But cutting down even the core content after years of delay? Inexcusable.EDIT:The Good:-incredibly strange and unique world.-story is alright so far, it's fun and enjoyable to work through.-Side quests and characters are so interconnected that plot threads feed the living world quite well.- Background detail is sufficient.- Background music is good.The Bad:-Combat is a boring slog, it doesn't come up often though which just means 1/3 of the characters skills and uniqueness is pointless in this game.-UI : The game is clearly rushed in terms of UI/UX polish.-AI: Path finding is Bugged as hell. Often lose a character because they get stuck running into other characters and objects.- AI: Combat AI is pointless, never had a fight which is interesting from a tactics point. Considering the few amount of fights in the game I was hoping they would all be very unique.-Settings: For a game built on the Pillars tech, it sure lacks settings and options.- Virtually Silent: this game has no sound bar the one time I heard voice acting , and the very subtle background noises now and then.CONCLUSION:A decent RPG but no where near what the ""Big Name Reviewers"" are promising. But it if you have a hankering for new weird locations to read about and explore.If you are looking for a decent CRPG experience then look at Pillars of Eternity instead.This game lacks a serious amount of polish and design. The story is good and the amount of detail sufficient but the gameplay elements are very lacklustre.If the game was never ""about combat"" then why bother spending your limited time and resources fleshing out a combat mechanic?Game could've been so much more , but threw away too much in pursuit of a ""great story""."
76561198046671600,Not Recommended,272270,30305466,Posted: 3 March,all,gideonscanlon,"Four years after its record-breaking crowdfunding campaign, and more than two years after its planned release date, Torment: Tides of Numenera has arrived. Fans of Planescape: Torment had long looked forward to the game’s release, excited by the opportunity to play an isometric RPG with a focus on thoughtful story-telling, compelling characters set against a bizarre backdrop. Today, those fans are decidedly underwhelmed.Let me be clear, this game is not awful, but it pales in comparison to many of its ‘isometric rpg renaissance’ peers, and comes across more as an awkward imitation of the original Torment than a loving tribute. While the backdrop of the ‘Ninth World’ echoes the oddness of Planescape setting well, the games are otherwise very different.Where the 1999 game’s plot was engaging, surprising and satisfying, Tides of Numenera’s is thin, obvious and quite forgettable. Where the Nameless One kept company with a floating skull, a demoness and a mechanical box-thing, the Last Castoff will journey with people that many orthodontists would find to be a bit dreary.It is not just the game’s writing that leaves much to be desired. The action – rare as it is – is maddeningly slow and repetitive. The character generation system – which initially seems to offer a great deal of choice – has very little impact on the game. Even the vaunted ‘tides’ morality system, which appears to have the potential to add depth to your character’s choices, has little more than a cosmetic impact on the game.Reader, if you are hoping to recapture Planescape: Torment’s unusual approach to adventuring, this game will be a terrible disappointment... but dry those tears. A few month ago, rival game studio Obsidian Entertainment beat InXile to the punch, releasing a bizarre isometric RPG of their own. While Tyranny’s setting is far less similar to Planescape than Tides of Numenera's, it entertains in a very similar way. Characters include a haunted suit of armour and a mind-absorbing maniac named ‘The Voices of Nerat.’Skip this, get that. Don’t let InXile get away with phoning in such a promising idea – especially after the crowdfunding efforts, the two year delay and the big selling job."
