,Not Recommended,272270,30293964,Posted: 3 March,all,nano.Luo Tianyi,"As someone who have played the original source material (Numenera RPG, the tabletop one) before. This one is hard for me. inXile did put a breath of life to the Ninth World fantastically. The world, the background are weird and odd, but carry the abstractly beautiful aesthetic that is a throwback to the old games like Myst, Oddworld, and The Longest Journey. However, the story, dialogue, and bad adaption of tabletop system kills the fun for me.Story is good, but not really something to write home about. Maybe I did set the bar too high, but it did not leave a strong lasting impression. It will entice you to follow it, but sometime I get bored and just quit the game. Instead of wanting to get to the end on my own, it feels more like a carrot on a stick. Also I do not like most of the companions as a person. That maybe a good or bad thing because I do not know how others do find them. I feel that they are really unlikable, almost Anti-Mary Sue like unlikable. I do not see anything good in them at all. Everyone except for theLost Child who Talks to God, and the Furtive Jack who Murders.One thing I really appreciate about this is inXiles decision to separate the continuity from the source material because lately it has been cancerous lately not so subtly pushing political agenda, but also to let the uninitiated have an easy time understanding this weird little world.Dialogue carries the worst sin in this game. For the denizens of the Ninth World, they sure do speak and behave like typical Hipsters and the Millenials of San Francisco of today. Not all of them, sure. But when I came across one, the magic is shattered and the wonders fade. The other times, it just feel odd. I understand that this is the future world where everything is eerie and weird, but I just cannot seem to relate. Star Trek and other Speculative Fictions also do boast weird alien cultures, but it is done well. Not in this case though.The gameplay. Where should I begin, this will be a long topic. First, how about lack of character customisation though your mileage may vary with this one. Planescape: Torment is an old game, lack of customisation is excusable for the game of that period. I feel this is a missed opportunity, even though 'your appearance is a plot point', so why the so called plot point cannot follow the player customisation. Why the devs do not let players have fun express themselves properly through the 'Role-Playing' game. I seriously do not want to be some guy with bad tan and a bad hairdo.Second, the severe lack of Foci option. You only have 3 foci which is not really much, the source material has about 30 which I believe can be easily translated. Why I cannot be a Jack who WIelds Two Weapon or Wields Power with Precision, or a Nano who Explores Dark Places.Third, the introduction of HP, stunted starting pool, lack of Edge in the beginning. The Cypher system is simple enough to translate to video game format without much difficulty, yet the dev decided to 'adapt it to video game' and the work did screw up the balance and fun of the system. For the uninitiated, the source material has no HP. Any damage you sustain goes into the appropriate pool (mental assault hits Intellect, a hamstring hits Speed, a slash hits Might), if the appropriate pool are depleted then it goes to the next appropriate. If one pool is depleted, you are in big trouble with a penalty to every action. If two pools are depleted, you are near death as in utterly covered bruises and bleeding or something along that line, can take no action and can only crawl. Three gone, you are dead. No need to introduce HP at all. Your starting pool are higher (average out at 9-10), and you begin with appropriate Edge or two of your chosen class so that, say a Nano can use Onslaught with for free without having to run to inn every time he depletes his pool (and put himself in a bad situation). Also you have 6 Tiers and recover your pool through recovery pool, not magical inn rest that cures everything including AIDS.This will be direct questions to the dev:I poked around the inner workings, I just want to ask why? I saw that you were going for a 1-1 translation of the game, so why everything ended up half-baked. Dangers of Kickstarter of having to listen 100 opinions pushing you 100 directions as a designer so you have to compromise to satisfy everyone but in the end let everyone down? Also the 'hand-crafted' combat encounters is too heavy handed, let thing flow, give some space for players to work with please.Everything feels like a giant half-hearted of a letdown in attempt to please everyone. Not every customer wants what they say they want, you are game designer, developers. You should know these situations well where if you let a customer just use you as a tool which is precisely commanded through feedback, then the end result is going to be bad.No more please. Never again.Message to the devs ends hereTo summarise. I would not recommend this. It is fun, charming, lovely, but ultimately a massive letdown and you see a fleeting grand vision of what could have been a magnificent masterpiece, a disappointment you cannot let go like an ex with a tragic breakup."
76561198032171700,Recommended,272270,28266214,"Posted: 8 December, 2016",all,mrhagel,"Ah, Tides of Numenera.This game has great potential. It -can- become a truly great game. Perhaps one of the all-time greats.But we are not there yet. The game as it stands in December 2016 is a 10-hour buggy mess with a crappy combat system.So how come I recommend it do you say? Well, here's why. It -does- have great potential. The story is engrossing, the world is strange, mystical, and refreshing, the skills and abilities are cool and, for the most part, work really well. The combat system is an exception. It doesn't work well, and doesn't feel slick and dangerous, like combat should.Without going into spoilers I want to say that the main story so far looks really well put together. There are many throwbacks to Planescape: Torment, but this is definitely its own thing.The three-stat system, and how you use stats for skills and conversations all work really well.There's a lot of bugs in the current build, and hopefully by the time you read this review, they have ironed out the worst of them. I expect a lot of this game. I count on inXile to deliver."
