76561197992681922,Recommended,272270,30238199,Posted: 28 February,all,SirLogiC,"I recommended this game, butit is definitely not for everyone. Planescape: Torment was like reading a book in game form. As the Spiritual successor Torment: Tides of Numenera (T:ToN) is the same. So if you aren't into dialogue heavy games then this is not for you.The writing is very good though. It is interesting. Sometimes it feels to me like there is some trying hard to be different and exotic, but mostly it's excellent.Combat is done fairly interestingly. You ""spend"" your stat points to perform actions, or boost them. Then use consumables or rest to restore them.Ciphers are special consumables, you can only carry a limited amount, or you get penalties, and they are one use only. But you get enough that I don't really get the ""I'll save this for when I need it"" hoarding.Annoted my logbook."
76561197994989613,Not Recommended,272270,30340923,Posted: 5 March,all,JackLuminous,"Too much text, not enough gameplay. They say good dialogue is what made Planescape great. They're not wrong, but what they didn't understand is that what kept the original from being a true masterpiece was the lack of decent combat gameplay. I remember playing it and by the end thinking ""man, what a great story, great characters and intriguing world... now if only it had the combat gameplay mechnanics of Baldur's Gate, it would have been the best"". Instead of correcting this, they made it worse. I can't play this 10 minutes without getting bored and rushing through dialogues and without the dialogues, there's nothing left. Show, don't tell. I find it ironic that whenever you ask a character a second time to repeat the trivial information he spent so long to describe he manages to summarize it in a few sentences only. These summary, more often than not, should have been the first and only answer.The fact that you can't engage in combat with anyone also diminishes the impression of freedom and choice of action and reinforces the impression that you're really just a spectactor here, and the game just wants you to go about speaking to people and solve their fetch quests. Whatever your choices in Baldur's Gate, you knew you could always attack the npcs. Here? The game really just wants you to listen to its lore...I don't recommend it. This is for hipsters stuck on nostalgia saying that PT was about something else than gameplay. PT was great but it's never been the classic game than Baldur's Gate was. It could have been so much better with a better combat mechanic and simply MORE COMBATS.I understand PT strived to be the ANTI Baldur's Gate, and had its heart in the right place by having you focus in stats like charisma, intelligence and wisdom instead, but it went overboard with it, as it ends up way less balanced than BG and having little replay value. Fights is what give replay value to these games. Fights can go in so many directions, although less so in turn based combats, but that's another issue (at this point I'm just desperate for anything else than listening to NPCs narrating a fantasy's short story, so I'll take turn based, even with its obvious flaws). Dialogues options, on the other hand, is just a matter of reloading and finding out what happens if I click on one answer instead of the other. They are ""nice to have"", but they're not the meat of these video games.Unfortunatly they chose poorly in this sequel by focusing even LESS on gameplay. I guess it costs less to produce. 50$ for this is ridiculous. It's worth 15$ at the most. Will not be purchasing from InXile again."
