,Recommended,272270,25959802,"Posted: 9 October, 2016",all,#divideby8,"As someone who has more than 300 hours into Pillars, I can say that I am not too excited for Tides.Pillars easily carries the most coheisve and dramatically presented narrative in a cRPG since Baldur's Gate 2, yet while Tides holds it's place in my library, I earnestly do not expect it to hold up as well.inXile games tend to carry a very unfinished and unpolished feel to them, which is often overlooked due to quality writing that propells the games from start to finish. Wasteland 2 is an excellent example of this: great story ... but incomplete ""product"" ... and the hours I've spent with the Early Access of Tides, I get the same impression.Recent changes have shown a clear trajectory towards simple delivery of a complex story, confirmed by developer responses on the forums to questions regarding removed features (such as a truncated introduction that has been stripped of any ingenuity and unique inspiration that it had during earlier versions). Many suspect this is due to it's concurrent console release, but I suspect there is more to it: as development has unfolded, I believe the inXile scrapped elements that weren't working, which has left visceral gaps in what remains.Still, inXile's writers are top notch and I will play this game through to the end, but I do not expect it to have much of the replayability that PlaneScape: Torment, Baldur's Gate/2, or Pillars of Eternity possess."
