,Not Recommended,272270,33198804,Posted: 3 July,all,Dustcloud,"Sooo.......... Ages ago I backed this game on Kickstarter. However, once InExile started making development decisions that seemed to reverse promises made in the Kickstarter I became skeptical. Only having backed for a $20 digital game didn't make it worth refunding. But I felt as though there were intrinsic aspects of Infinity Engine-style games, and Torment in Particular, that the developers either didn't understand, or wanted to shortcut, and that these decisions were exemplified by their conception of ""Crisis Encounters"" and turn-based mechanics.Well, after finally playing the game, I feel that me concerns were eminently justified.The idea that you should be able to interact with characters and the environment to resolve encounters makes toooooooooons of sense, and it's good to see. But mixing it with turn-based mechanics is a terrible, awful, no-good, and vile fundamental flaw. The Torment devs think nothing of tossing a dozen random mobs into encounters that revolve around your characters essentially flipping a couple switches or have a few conversations without dying. You then find yourself taking thirty quadrillion zillion years per encounter to talk to a couple NPC people because you have to wait for all the mobs to cycle through their turns. Even worse, sometimes the AI bugs out during encounters and you have to restart the whole damned thing. (Not to mention some of their graphics and effects choices are weirdly non-performant relative to quality while at times being rather overdone and innelegant.)If they'd stuck to typical Infinity Engine-style ""Real Time With Pause"" during these things it'd have been fine. But they didn't, and it's miserable. Even weirder, there's no coherent reason for adopting the encounter system: the game isn't remotely a tactical turn based game like XCOM or something. And bringing that style of gameplay into a game based less on combat and tactics and more on dialog and interactions makes no cohesive sense. What does the player gain out of enemies taking a dozen sequential turns when all that's going to happen is that you're going to flip a couple text-encounter switches and resolve them with some ""effort?""Now if you ignore the terrible terrible terrible encounters the game is actuall more than half-decent or even good. At least two of the companions are interesting (if a tad underdeveloped, which is weird and crazy considering the amount of text in the game). (Others are kind of boring.) The world is interesting. The plot is interesting, though at times hard to grasp if you aren't making sure to investigate every damn thing. This is a game that could have been great, but somebody tried to frankenstein the idea of ""turn based-encounters"" into what's fundamentally a mostly dialog-based game and it ruined it. Narratively, I think it really deserved to have the Last Castoff forge some more meaningful bonds with non-party based (particularly castoff) NPCs, and the lack of said meaningful bonds between the castoff and all but a couple in-party characters really makes some of the decisions fall flat, feel a bit empty. (I think the Merecaster thing was supposed to be a way to sidestep this issue, but I don't really feel like it worked.)If somebody could figure out a way to mod the encounters into behaving like combat in Pillars of Eternity or Baldur's gate the game would probably be many times better. Help me tan the dead horse's hide: ""It's just not fun to have to spend 1+ hours to have two conversations because of pointless turn-based mechanics."" I question devs who couldn't grasp this... They are certainly not ones I'd ever trust with what was essentially a preorder again.I feel bad writing this review because most games these days aren't remotely as interesting. Yet I'm not sure it's right to praise something so flawed just because the attempt was made and it is rather interesting...I definitely would love to see another RPG set in the Ninth World, at least."
