76561198005989331,Recommended,272270,29341976,Posted: 18 January,all,Erebus,"First some background:""Planescape: Torment"" has been my favorite CRPG of all time since I first played it at its release in 1999.It figuratively and literally turned the genre on its head. All the basic assumptions people take away from most CRPGs had been practically inverted wholesale.I was a fan of the source tabletop setting released in 1994, long before the game hit the shelves, so I had looked at the video game with a very critical eye, and found every moment of its game play engaging, and its story, theme and characters utterly unique.I was hesitant, and ultimately decided against supporting the kickstarter, mostly as I realize now due to my lack of understanding of the Numenera setting. Unlike Planescape, which had the underpinnings of D&D to start with, I was never able to wrap my head around how the Numenera setting worked. It just never clicked for me.Initial Impressions:I knew I’d pick this up when it released, even if it was just a chance of catching some of that old Planescape:Torment nostalgia.I also admit, I only have 3.0 hours, yes three, into this as I'm writing it. (I may update this review after I have more time with the actual release version).However, I've played the first 10-20 minutes of the game probably 6 times, each with completely different outcomes:In some I died prior to even getting into a fightIn others I was able to talk down my foesI used environment objects to help me overcome my enemiesI’ve pretended to be someone I’m notIn others I was painfully truthful to my own detriment.From what I've seen, which I completely admit is a small sliver of the whole, this not only matches my expectations of what a spiritual successor to P:T would be, it exceeds them.The settings are equally fantastic in the truest sense of the word. The characters I’ve seen so far, are almost as good as the initial characters you meet in P:T.If the rest of this game matches the first 15 minutes, this will easily slide up to match Planescape:Torment as my favorite cRPG.Where Planescape: Torment asked: “What can change the nature of a man?”Torment: Tides of Numenera asks: “What does one life matter?”And as in P:T, Ibelievelooking forward this justmayhelp you answer that question in the same way,through game play, story, and character development."
