,Not Recommended,272270,30352331,Posted: 6 March,all,Subspace Dandy,"Perfect world-building, good storyline, very interactive (but zero real player agency and probably not much replay value).Main problem: it's obviously rushed. It feels as if at some point they decided to stitch all the finished fragments and systems of a much larger game into something smaller and passable enough to sell. That, among other things, screwed up the pacing and rendered half of the systems obsolete.The end result has merits, but it is not very graceful.Too bad. Could've been an excellent game; instead it's merely decent (not a crime, but even if you disregard the hype the wasted potential is glaringly obvious).Clearly needed another year (or two). A large addon, maybe? Some sort of director's cut? Sadly, that's not likely to happen."
,Not Recommended,272270,30539492,Posted: 16 March,all,Kiyo,"I haven't finished the game and I'm writing this review now because I'm not sure that I will. It's a decent game, but when you set yourself up as the successor to Planescape: Torment, you have to live up to high expectations, and Tides of Numenera just doesn't. The concept and world are amazing, but the implementation is just unfinished, making the experience feel like you're just scratching the sruface.First, here's what the game does right. I really liked the original story. It's a bit of a slow burn, but most of the writing is good, and they included all the interesting and bizarre little details, side-stories, and dark humor that really nailed the same narrative feel as PS:T. Also, the promise of being able to take multiple approaches to situations has been delivered. They also definitely brought it with the art. The various game locations I've seen so far are varied and exciting, and in the era of 3D dominance, they still manage to make an isometric game look attractive and visually engaging.However, the flaws really prevent this game from coming together into an immersive experience. The idea of the tides affecting how everyone in the world reacts to you was barely there, really just adding up to a few throwaway dialogue lines of, ""I had heard you were that type of person..."" It never seemed to actually affect outcomes. Also, there are no real factions like the ones you could interact with and even join in Torment. I ""joined"" one of the groups in the game through dialogue, but it has had no effect at all as far as I can tell. No one treated me any differently, I got no stat bonuses or penalties, it didn't seem to help or hurt the group's standing in the world, and I later I even met people who were members of that same group and they had no idea who I even was. Again, there was a lame line about how the various branches of the group didn't have much contact with each other.The skills, abilities, and effort setup felt needlessly complex, and some of the mechanics were never fully explained. I never figured out how to tell the difference between a one-handed and a two-handed weapon except by equipping it, and I'm still not sure why weapons were divided up into heavy and light. I don't need a lot of hand-holding or a huge tutorial, but as far I can tell, this info wasn't available for me to see anywhere at all. It sucks having to buy a weapon just to see if my character can use it with his shield, then having to sell it back at a loss when it turns out it's two-handed. Maybe I missed something. Finally, I encountered a bug that would cause combat to freeze periodcially. It didn't happen every combat, but several of the bigger ones I had to keep reloading and replaying, which was really tedious. It's a known issue, but a fix doesn't seem to be forthcoming.I really, really, wish they had fleshed this game out a little more. There was so much promise and if they could have polished it a bit more and made sure that the player's choices had more of an impact on the game world, it would have equaled or even surpassed its ""spiritual"" predecessor."
76561197993815207,Not Recommended,272270,30475608,Posted: 12 March,all,(╯°□°）╯︵ ┻━┻,"I've encountered a lot of bugs that cause the game to lock up and freeze, forcing you to play through parts of the game multiple times.  The combat mechanics are pretty simplistic.  Character development isn't very interesting.  The setting is interesting; the storyline is decent; the NPCs are imaginative in description if not in visual presentation.  It's not a good game, but it's a decent experience.  I wouldn't have paid full price for this game though if I had known then what I do now."
,Not Recommended,272270,30919519,Posted: 3 April,all,Truck-Sama,"This is a difficult game to recommend or not recommend.  I'll start off by prefacing: don't buy the game if you expect something on the level of PS:T or BG1-2. It doesn't compare to those favorably at all.As for the actual review, there are a lot of good things going for the game. The world is extremely well developed and rich in lore. I greatly enjoyed just reading all the flavor text spread liberally throughout the game. The story, while nothing unique, is sufficient as a vehicle to get the player through the game. Best of all, the game actually means it when it says you can build any type of character and be successful at clearing the game. I fought a total of four times in the entire game. Then there are the characters, most of which have interesting back stories and designs.Unfortunately, there's a lot to dislike too. While the characters ARE interesting, they're also extremely flat. They never truly progress anywhere with the exception of one, and you only see that development at the very end for a brief moment. Then there's all the lore text: it's ♥♥♥♥ing massive, the equivalent of a hefty novel all on it's own. The combat system is hit or miss, as well, though credit is due to the game as it does allow you to talk your way through even combats. The ending is also unbelievably boring, just a brief conversation at the very end with a generic ""This is what happened after..."" slideshow for the epilogue.I think the worst of it all, however, is just how short the game is. I read through all the flavor text and took my time doing all the quests available and I still finished the game in less than 25 hours. Admittedly, I'm a quick reader, but that's pretty pathetic for a 45 dollar RPG. There's not much replay value to it either, as despite what it says your choices don't actually affect much throughout the game outside of maybe some flavor things.Overall, I'd recommend it if you can get it on sale for about 20 dollars. Otherwise, just wait for it to go on sale or see if inXile  is releasing some amazing DLC or a modding system or something."
