76561198062284493,Recommended,272270,30298904,Posted: 3 March,all,lukasz.sam,"Uhh... that's rather hard recommendation to give but I'm gonna recommend it despite the fact that this game is very much flawed - and that's recommendation only for people that already played Planescape: Torment. If you didn't - go play it now and if you like it and want more of it then consider Tides of Numenera.Why? Because Tides of Numenera is fundamentally an echo, imitation ... a castoff of true masterpiece. It has similar themes, similar structure, protagonist in similar situation and even some similar weaknesses (combat is weakest part of both games), but its just not as good.You can say that is what we wanted: another Torment, but at the same time I feel like this game could be quite a lot better if it would told its own story, something new, different and weird, something unique.So what worked and what didn't?Setting - both Planescape and Numenera are weird, but weird in very good way, both are colorful and exotic but also dark, twisted and cruel when they need to. So while I feel that Planescape with stronger focus on beliefs and philosophies is better of two, both settings are great.Cities - both games are very much city-centric and cities in Tides are just as great as Sigil. Definitely best part of this game is exploring Cliffs and Bloom (especially Bloom), talking to their inhabitants and solving their problems.Story - just as I wrote earlier  Tides of Numenera tries hard to tell similar story to PT instead of creating something unique. Effects are well... serviceable, but I doubt I will even remember it in few months. Thankfully side quests and conversations were well written and generally interesting.Companions - while I rather liked all companions i traveled with they are rather uninspired... I'mean you have that wonderfully weird settings and all of the companions are human? Why? PT gave us flying skull, succubus-turn-good, walking suit of armor and other just as unique personas... why in Tides we don't travel in company of mutants, sentient machines or otherworldy creatures with utterly alien perspectives on current events?Combat - combat was weak in PT... its actually even worse in Tides - at least  as mage in PT you have tons of interesting spells, most powerful of which even had their own pre-rendered cut-scenes. Here your abilities are boring, your opponents are boring and stupid, strategical depth is non-existent, everything is way too easy (and there is no difficulty setting) unless you are outnumbered and your opponents will be first in initiative and straight up murders half of your party before your first move. Its probably worst combat I've seen in any cRPG (with exception of some really low budget indie).Graphic - character models and effects (i.e. spells) are poor, backgrounds... some are quite good, some lack polish, few are weak. I don't want to compare Tides and PT because of age difference - so instead I'm going to say that Tides looks little worse than Pillars of Eternity or Tyranny, but still good enough."
