76561198050827199,Not Recommended,272270,30347504,Posted: 5 March,all,Telmah,"This game is a fraud and I would recommend against buying it.I go back a long time with Planescape: Torment, so I was ecstatic when I learned about the kickstarter for Tides. Naturally, I became a backer of this game during the kickstarter and eagerly waited to start playing it. Having finished the first playthrough, I am sorely disappointed. Before I explain why, I'd like to point out that this game is extremely text-heavy and players who aren't prepared to spend about 80% of their time reading should avoid it regardless of the reviews being positive or negative.My main source of frustration is the fact that the devs cut the content that had been promised in the Kickstarter project. I understand that this isn't rare regarding crowdfunding, but it is a scummy, dishonest business policy and borderline fraud which would prevent me from recommending this game even were it good, and it isn't.To give credit where credit is due, the game mechanics are pretty solid. From character development to the item system,  Tides of Numenera is a streamlined, yet complex RPG. There are some improvements that could have been made, but the game is very satisfactory from a game mechanics perspective. Still, Planescape: Torment's best and most important attribute was the story, and Tides is pretty weak in that regard. Firstly, the game is very short. My playthrough was pretty thorough, yet I was finished about 30 hours in. For a game which spent so long a period in development and whose Kickstarter was considered a major success, I consider anything less than 50 hours a disappointment, and I was hoping for something like The Witcher 3, where you could easily spend 100 hours.*the rest of the review contains spoilers*Leaving behind game mechanics, I will comment on the story from the perspective of the plot, setting and the underlying philosophy.The setting is bizarre and interesting and has a proper tormentesque vibe. It is based on a tabletop roleplaying game by Monte Cook, and I will gladly take the game up if I ever return to pen and paper gaming. At times the game was a tad too bizarre for my taste, but this isn't a major minus and many people will probably like it. The plot is a good fit for the general style of the game and the setting. Although it is nothing near to being spectacular, the small amount of story this game has is pretty good.What makes the game intrinsically bad is the superficial philosophy behind it, despite several neat touches, such as the Lascar side-quests symbolizing religion. The primary question, ""What does one life matter?"", is tied to the primary story in a very loose way. One problem is the fact that this question is very wide, especially in comparison to the question posed by Planescape: Torment, ""What can change the nature of a man?"" PsT's question was interwoven in the storyline and by the time Ravel asks for your answer you have had plenty of time to seedifferent perspectives on this problem. In Numenera, the question feels forced. If we ignore wild interpretations and the places where such a wide question is inherently linked to the standard fantasy themes, it is hard to see how it relates to the primary story beyond the two times it is directly asked. Even when it is inherent in some problem which often appears in fantasy games, it doesn't seem to be significantly more developed than usual. What I felt was the main philosophical point of the story is a rather lame bioconservative eulogy of death. In very short and simple terms, The Changing God is fighting to prolong his life and The Sorrow tells you that prologing one's life inherently harms other people, so it should be stopped. I don't think that there is an ending which is further from this philosophy than the one I chose, and in my ending The Sorrow and the Last Castoff agreed not to kill any castoffs at that time, but The Sorrow forbade the creation of any further castoffs and also promised to slaughter them later on. This kind of ending is highly unsatisfying, especially as I wasn't very interested in the internal castoff-changing god issues since I perceived The Sorrow as the primary enemy. Although I could say that I am a quite radical transhuanist on the issue of death, I would be more than interested to see a nuanced bioconservative argument in this sort of a game. The problem is that the argumentation present in Numenera is quite flimsy and reductible to saying that simply living is harming other people. Even this argumentation lies on a very symbolic reading of the Tides, but without it I would be hard pressed to find one developed central philosophical argument in the entire game. In that respect, the philosophy of the game is quite under-developed even if my interpretation is lacking. Of course, I am open to the possibility that I missed something, but I feel that the philosophical background of the game is simply bad. The solid but short story and mecahincs don't compensate for this deficit in my books.tldr; Regardless of the story, I wouldn't recommend Tides of Numenera because of the dishonest business practice regarding its Kickstarter project. The setting is great and the story and mechanics of the game are reasonably sound, although the story is very short. But the philosophical background, which is crucial for a Torment game, is lacking and that makes the entire game unsatisfying. Despite the negative review, the story and especially the setting are interesting enough to potentially be of interest if you could get the game at a significant discount, for something like 10-15$."
,Not Recommended,272270,30395214,Posted: 8 March,all,TheRaven7,"there's 6 endings and all of them are badnone of them are tied to the choices you make the whole game so it's basically Mass Effect 3 times 2the game itself is not just a spiritual successor to Planescape: Torment, but copies so much at points you start calling characters by the names from the first gameit's still somewhat fun to play but if you're hoping for an experience on par with Planescape: Torment, pass or wait for this game to be on deep sale"
76561198019283303,Recommended,272270,35170733,Posted: 23 September,all,cowcrusher,"If you know what to expect, this is an absolutely amazing, uniquely original, and thoroughly rewarding game. If you’re expecting nail-biting combat, labyrinthian skill trees, oodles of loot, and a robust class system…this is not the game for you. However, if you’re after detailed and rich storytelling, complex characters, and an immersive and unexpected world that demands your focus and attention, then look no further.In some ways, I was fortunate in coming to this game late, as it gave me a chance to read lots of reviews and reactions. I can definitely understand how it may have been mis-marketed early on, setting up some false expectations, but I think enough time has passed that the game can be understood and judged for what is now, rather than for what people were expecting it to be.Furthermore, I was actually drawn to this game specifically due to some of the things that others have complained about. Chiefly: the insane amount of text (serious, this makes War and Peace look like a pamphlet), and the lack of combat. In short, this game offers an alternate take on what an RPG can be, and that’s exactly what I was looking for.Still, there are pros and cons. Other reviews here have done a better job of this, but here are some that stand out for me.I really like how combat is handled. An encounter is called a “crisis”, and there are multiple ways to resolve it that don’t require fighting. Essentially, based on how you want to play the game and types of characters you build, you can choose to either take a social approach (lie, bribe, intimidate, etc), a mechanical approach (lore, repair, manipulating things), or the old standby of fighting. This gave me more choices as to how I wanted to play a scenario, based on how I was feeling at that time, and it also gives the game more replayability. My first play through (based on someone else’s advice) focused on the social skills (I basically lied my way through most encounters, which was great), but now I’m curious to go through again with a different focus. And, as I said, it’s nice to take a break from hack-n-slash once in a while. The flipside is that each crisis, no matter what approach you take, is unfairly stacked against you. Things usually go terribly wrong (you’re always outnumbered, never have enough supplies, and AI is irritating). You will die a lot, but that’s actually the point. Much like Planescape, death is merely a gateway to another realm, with it’s own set of quests and characters and things to do, and then you can easily re-enter the world of the living and try again (note that there are a few deaths which are permanent, so saving frequently is still a good idea).The other criticism of combat is true: there isn’t much of it. For a game of this length, there are probably no more than a dozen crisis encounters. Maybe that’s an exaggeration, but combat was very, very, very few and far between. However, each crisis is a major event, so they make up for frequency with complexity. Some of the encounters can require a long-haul commitment and take quite a while to get through, so that also makes up for the lack of numbers.Now, if the lack of combat is a turn off for you, then it’s best to give the game a pass. However, in my opinion, it more than makes up for the reduced role that fighting takes, by expanding on some of the other things that role playing can offer. Things like story, character building, choices, exploration, interactions, are all extremely rich, detailed and rewarding.And I suppose that’s where the other justified criticism comes in. All of the aforementioned role playing elements are almost entirely text based. Yes this is a modern game with visuals, sounds, and UI…but the heart is un-abashedly old-school text. Seriously, reams and reams of it. However, the writing is, with few exceptions, fantastic. And sometimes, the images conjured in my imagination are more powerful than anything a visual could render. The scenes, descriptions, ideas, dialog and details are simply mesmerizing. This is a thoroughly constructed and very deep world. It is worth every syllable.You do run into some hammy lines now and then, but considering the sheer volume of text, a few throw-away phrases hardly dent the epicness of the whole. I can’t stress enough just how rich and imaginative this game is. There are enough ideas in here for a hundred games, if not more. Some are fanciful, others disturbing, and yet others quite profound.  Ultimately whatever you do think of the game, there are many ideas and images in here that will stay with you for a very long time. Maybe haunt is the better word. This is also true to the mood of the game, as it is just as cruel as it is verbose. This is a painful, spiteful, gruesome, and utterly disgusting world that you are inhabiting. Nothing turns out well, for anyone, ever. But it’s also insatiably riveting.The only other complain that I might add, which isn’t a bad thing depending on your viewpoint, is that items and trade are rather disappointing. There is finite number of items in the this game, and finite number of merchants who have a finite amount of money. Maybe I’m just spoiled by games where looting is a reward, and trading is a skill. Not so here. If you get carried away and use up all the healing potions, life will suck for you, as there are no more. And the merchants are dirt poor, so you’re never going to get rich, which is fine as there’s nothing of interest to buy anyway. The most coveted objects in the entire game world are the Numenera themselves. These are basically single purpose objects that can do amazing, deadly, or powerful things in combat and beyond. And the whole Numenera system is really cool and well executed in the game…BUT there are just so darn few of them in the world that I wound up hoarding them, rather than using them, because I wasn’t sure I’d ever find more. As for the weapons, there’s almost zero point in trying to upgrade. The difference it makes in a crisis is minimal, and there just aren’t many options to choose from. Not to say there aren’t surprises, the Merecasters are fun, for example. When activated they essentially launch you immediately into a mini side quest, a sort of choose-your-own-adventure. Depending on how you do, you might gain a bonus or something from them, plus they’re a nice departure from the main narrative.Despite any minor flaws, I definitely recommend this game to anyone looking to try something that’s beyond the rote RPG. It’s very rare for me to want another playthrough of a game. But I do have to honestly say that I will revisit Torment in the future, and I wish there were more like it. Imagination will always be more powerful than spectacle."
