,Not Recommended,272270,30728528,Posted: 25 March,all,chiffaN,"Hey Folks,First of all I would like to give a shoutout to all the wonderful developers over at InXile who made a bold attempt at bringing a true spiritual successor to one of the best RPGs of all time - Planescape Torment.The road to hell is paved by good intentions...I have been psyching myself up to do this review for some time now, it's been around a week or so since I finished Torment. Also, I would like to note that I have not been an original backer, though I did pledge around mid 2015 directly on the site. I am highlighting this to mark that I have not been emotionally involved in the Kickstarter process and have no idea about the stretch goals and the subsequent delivery on those.I have thoroughly enjoyed PS:T back in the days and loved Wasteland 2 even before the directors cut came out, which made all the better.Pre-game:I know it sounds a bit stupid, but the Main Menu screen looks like it has been done by High School student. It threw me off whenever I booted up the game. I very much enjoyed the way the game preselected a character type for you based on a series of answers and I actually ended up playing the proposed one. But the lack of appearance customization just plain killed me. I couldn't even choose a portrait!!!Graphics:I played on my work laptop with built-in Intel Graphics so I definitely did not have the chance to experience the full power of T:ToN. The backgrounds and environment looked gorgeous, though all of the characters - much less so. And for some strange reason the vast majority of NPCs are actually missing any kind of portrait. Combine this with poorly detailed models, zoomed out screen and literally walls of text you end up feeling like reading a book rather than playing a game. Imagination has to run wild, otherwise there is simply no connection.General Gameplay:I actually very much enjoyed the stat pool mechanic, it felt like an interesting and fresh approach. That said the balance is completely off, nanos rule supreme, majority of stat checks are Intelligence and you can actually brute force the rest just by having enough stat pool points available.I made my playthrough opting for a non violent route and I could I mostly got away with it safe for a few hard coded battles where I could actually resolve them in a nonviolent matter within the Crisis itself. But make no mistake, I did not like those moments or solutions as they felt forced and breaking the pace of the game.Combat:Speaking about the pace - any combat is just horribly slow. Every enemy turn took at least 4-5 seconds just to get them moving!!! Having a mage-like characters I never felt underpowered but I was dissapointed with the variety of spells and weapons at my disposal. And the cyphers were just plain dumb - I haven't used a single one during the game. Overall the combat felt like a last minute add-on on top of the game just for the sale of having it without any proper mechanic or item support.Story:The overall plot while not a revelation by any stretch of the imagination is decent with a nice twist or two. The companions however are a complete disgrace. There is no romantic interest, the dialogues do not get further than 2 levels down. There is only 1 quest per companion and even those are just solved almost automatically as you clear out the game areas.The dying mechanic - a cornerstone of PS:T is completely tagged on just for show. It's a struggle even just to get killed, but when you do - it's a smallLabyrinth area with nothing to do there safe for a couple of 10min sidequests of kill/stun them allThe overarching plot itself is far too short, progressing in leaps as you move from one area to the other. I absolutely loved the depth of the world hinted at but T:ToN failed miserably in exploring it. All information is given in walls and walls of text. And don't even get me started on the Meres.They are just lazy game development. On one hand they require you to do tons of reading and tough choices, without hinting on what is a better/worse one and absolutely NO RETURN. That's right, you need to spend up to half-hour reading, hoping the stat pool check pan out, etc just to have zero impact back in the game. No perks or loot or anything. Initially I thought that after  you finish a mere the respective castoff would appear in the labyrinth. Nope.Interface:Is just plain horrible. The text is prevalent up to occupying almost half of the screen when in dialog. The inventory screen is dominated by the cypher section, which almost is useless. The amount of equippable slots on the characters is akin to an action/rpg and the inventory itself is showing no more than 2 rows at a time. Also, during the game you come upon a lot of items, called oddities, which are very confusing as what to do with them. Some you are able to use and even get a permanent bonus, others you can transform to artifacts, some you can actually use in quests.  So it's difficult to tell what you can safely sell. Which in the end is not that much of a problem since anyway there is little interesting to buy.Summary:However much I wanted to love it I was very much dissapointed with T:ToN. And it was made even worse because I saw that with just a few shifts in priorities in presentation and story it could've been so much better. The sheer amount of writing has come before everything else. Walls and walls of text meet you everywhere. If some of that effort was spent on expanding the item list, the skills and abilities, the companion quests, the portraits and overall locations  - it would have been a much more enjoyable experience.Queue: rotten tomatoes."
