76561197970252509,Recommended,272270,30322406,Posted: 4 March,all,Sajt,"What is the worth of a single life?My very first boxed PC game was Baldurs Gate. Then over the years I played every great Crpg. Fallout, Icewind Dale, Planescape Torment, Arcanum, Pillars of Eternity and the most recent Tyranny. I have played and replayed these games and IM happy to say that Torment: Tides of Numenera is amongst the best of them.The Story is deep as the worlds lore. You have to leave some of your preconceptions behind and embrace the alien nature and laws of this world. Where aliens, otherworldly beings and mutants walk under the red Sun. If you are afraid of walls of text and lore then this game will not be for you. If you enjoy reading and learning about a brand new world you will adore Numenera.Gameplay is the weak point of the title. Combat can be fun and engaging, with varied party setups, builds and interesting weapons and items but the way its system works can be a drag slowing the pace greatly. I have to admire a game where I can end a combat scenario without killing a single enemy, where I can avoid combat altogether. During my entire playthrough I didn't even have 10 battles. There are some technical bugs, but nothing game breaking. (Lets not forget that Planescape Torments combat wasn't great...).As a last word Rhin is now atop one of my favorite npc's of all time. (If you think she is weak I can only laugh at you.)Cheers"
