76561198004754218,Recommended,272270,32409072,Posted: 14 June,all,thrawn235,"I think this Game doesn't deserve all the bad votes. It is a worthy successor to Planescape:Torment. I'd say, on a mechanical level its even far superior to Planescape. You can finish the whole game without killing anybody, and there is a lot of gameplay even in the dialog, Depending on your skills or your Tides (alignment) you get extra information or even extra dialog options. Also, depending on your Attributes and Skills, you can fail at certain dialog options. Deceiption or persuation for example.If there is a Conflict, very often, you have the option of interacting with the enviroment or even to talk to the Characters involved. Instead of mindlessly killing everything that moves. This is a huge step up from previous RPGs and i really like it.Like planscape:torment the world is very strange and hard to understand first, but also very interesting and beleivable. but, like in planescape, you will probably be confused at first and it'll take some time to get familiar. In both games it took a few attempts for me to really get into it.The story and the varius quests are very well designed, not only is there a massive amount of well written text in the game, a lot (probably even all) the questlines are connected to each other in a very clever way. One will probably notice it in the End of the game.The game has one unfortunate flaw though, that even planespace had to a lesser degree. And i think lots of the downvotes come from this flaw.It is a somewhat cold and cerebral game. Even though the quests, and the whole story are very dramatic at times, I missed the emotions, especially from the party members. The fact that there are no romantic options in the game also doesnt help this.(The End is probably one of the best examples of aformentioned problem...)Still, I think this is an excellent game, and a must play for any serious RPG fan. To find a better one, you have to go way back (planescape, baldurs gate2, fallout 1+2, and maybe the mass effect trilogy)"
,Recommended,272270,30267891,Posted: 1 March,all,Bv900,"Wow. So, as is usual with things like this, it seems people went into the game with vastly different expectations than what was being developed. If you look at the majority of negative reviews, you will noticed two things: First, an average time played of 1-2 hours which makes any opinions they have on it laughable. Second, the most frequent complaint seems to whining about the combat system. The game isn't about combat, in fact every single combat situation in the game can be resolved in an alternate way.Anyway, enough about Steam reviews being mindless dogpiling. How is the game itself?It's a worthy successor to Planescape: Torment I feel. There are lengthy conversations with interesting characters to be had, nearly all of the companions have their own quirks and peculiar 'things' about them, and the world itself is based on the setting of one of the best Tabletop RPGs in the past few years. Seriously, I can't really explain just how much the world itself is a character in this game, full of weird, mysterious and wonderful things.I'm also not sure what people are talking about when they're complaining about the game being too short, I'm still in the first city, am 7-8 or so hours in, and still haven't explored two entire districts of the city. I feel the people complaining about there only being a few areas must have rushed through the game and completed zero sidequests, talked to people, or explored.So yeah. If you're a fan of old school CRPGs, if you enjoy reading, and you're interested in one of the most unique game worlds in recent memory, you should pick this up."
