76561197992845181,Recommended,272270,30348927,Posted: 5 March,all,Headfirst,"I only have one problem with this game:You know that one level in every RPG? The one where you enter the ""dreamscape"" or the extra-planar pocket, the memory realm or go ""inside the computer?"" That one level that's full of a bunch of random nonesense, with all kinds of crazy art, and literally every single NPC you meet says stuff like, ""I'm the one who sees, but is unseen,"" or ""this is the nexus of all places, where anything is possible, all futures exist... or is it? Maybe, maybe not. Is it reality? What is reality? If a tree falls in the forest..."" You know, *that* chapter of the game that makes no sense but you can tell the developers thought they were being philosophical, edgy, and avant garde?EVERY SINGLE PART OF THIS GAME IS *THAT* PART.Every map is full of crazy nonsense. Every single character, from your companions and major antagonists to lowly shopkeepers and random street NPCs, is a red herring enigma rubik's cube that vomits a never-ending stream of sphinx riddles at you if you so much as introduce yourself. ""I'm the last of the first, doomed to walk the ever-dream of the nightmare labyrinth for all eternity. Want to buy some weapons or armor?"" The item descriptions go even further: ""This thing is unlike anything you've ever seen. It defies classification. It's made from something you don't recognize and it does something wildly unpredictable. You have no idea what this is or what it's for. It's worth 120 space bucks.""All that being said, I'm recommending this game for every other part they got right. The art is amazing, the sound and voice acting are great, the game system is clever, and I never encountered a single bug."
76561198012714746,Recommended,272270,30363462,Posted: 6 March,all,Overlord Byron,"A setting-rich, nuanced, intriguing, and sometimes profound RPG that's more of an interactive codex than a video game proper. It's a mishmash of mostly unrelated stories interwoven with setting as the common thread, and most--or perhaps  exclusively--rewarding to the sort of gamer who is comfortable with experiencing those stories by proxy and through dialogue. There's choice, but you often lack freedom. There's exploration that involves little actual travel. The game knows what it is, but what it is isn't for everyone, and whether or not you'll enjoy it comes down to how inclined you are to meet it on its own terms."
76561197965438273,Recommended,272270,30404886,Posted: 9 March,all,Nim O'Fre,"TL:DR: Like it’s predecessor, Tides of Numenera is both deep and unique. If you’re expecting something more superficial and action-packed, move on.  If, however, you’re willing to play and read a captivating story that seemingly takes place across myriad volumes of sci-fi novelettes, play on!Like Planescape: Torment, Tides of Numenera gives back what you bring in to it.  It is rich in story, and never lacking in intrigue.  The combat and graphics may not be what some people seem to have wanted, but if that's what you were looking for then you picked the wrong class of game. This is more of a tome of philosophy and diversity than your typical cRPG: it brings both familiar and alien perspective to life with a brilliantly creative writing style that is sure to captivate any willing imagination.  To that end, it is a perfect spiritual successor to PS:T.When I think back to PS:T, I think of all amazing stories that seemingly random NPCs would have to share about their travels across the planes and how their lives were irrevocable altered--for better or worse.  I wonder about the relationship of the protagonist and the antagonist, about the circumstances of the very mufti-faceted reality that governed the story’s landscape, and what can really change the nature of man. It has been nearly two decades and those stories and philosophies still resonate with me to this day.  I can confidently say that after my first play-through, clocking in at nearly 48 hours, T:ToN will be apart of my future in much the same way, and in some ways, maybe even more so.I’ve only played through once, but I know for certain that choices *do* matter in this game.  Not every NPC needs closure, and might not get it, so some choices my seem ‘empty’ because you don’t see your various cookie-cutter meta-moral status bars adjust.  You have to remember though, this game has stories within stories. And as I said, it gives back what you bring in. While it *may* not always find fruition in the game, I can well imagine the fate of someone who’s life I impacted, and how they may one-day tell their story to another pilgrim of the Ninth World (assuming of course, they are around to tell it) and I sure as hell would be quick to pick up a book that comes out related to *any* of the characters I came across in this game.  However, there are many quests, dialogue options, and interactions that I could have done *very* differently, or in a different sequence that would have made real changes to the story and future in a variety of ways.  Let’s just say I have *big* plans for experimentation on my second play-though.. admittedly I *will* need some time to let this play-through sink in before I dive in again.I have read other reviewers claim that the game is too short, or warn that it cuts off in a manner similar to Tyranny, and nearly every negative review has something to say about combat To those issues I can only expound upon the aforementioned: my first play-though was almost 50 hours, and I definitely missed stuff. I didn’t find the ending to be abrupt at all. I thought each act had perfectly adequate pacing for both the story and character stat progression—I had to measure out my actions carefully in act one, but by the last act I was confident I could handle whatever came my way.. except maybe the weight of my own choices.  While I loved Tyranny’s emphasis on choice and dialogue, I would feel remiss to lump these two games into the same category, T:ToN is far more story-intensive, and you can see that story through to the end. Like PS:T this is not an item-based game.  If you’ve played any turn-based cRPGs before then you know the drill: you’re going to have to wait a bit during a ‘crisis.’ I really only actually fought in probably half of the crises, but considering the crises make up about .01% of the game, I think the combat was challenging enough to warrant the circumstances leading up to them, and rewarding no matter how they ultimately played out..It is hard for me to review a game like this because, like a good book, it is really more of an intimate experience that begs lengthy discourse.  All I can really say is if you *do* decide to play this one, accept it for what it is--rather than how it’s *not* whatever else is out there--and really play it.  Get to *know* everyone, explore every nook and plunder every cranny.. interact with everything you can.. it will be worth it. Find out just how much you believe one life matters."
76561197999072624,Recommended,272270,30298472,Posted: 3 March,all,Beige&Confused,"This is initial thoughts/impressions.  I will post a proper review when I have spent more time with the game but I just want to get my thoughts in writing.First things First: this is easily my most anticipated game of the last couple years (I am literally playing this the day Zelda Breath of the Wild came out, that level of anticipation).  I played Planescape: Torment around 2011 and absolutley adored it, but was unable to finish it because of several game breaking glitches that I couldn't find my way around.  Still loved the game enough to be stupidly hyped for this.I have good and bad first impressions: The good is it captures the feel of the original with a world that is nearly (but not quite) as imaginitive and alien.  The combat system is INSTANTLY better and is no longer the mindless chaos that a lot of old CRPG battle systems tend to be.  The interface is deep but also accessible, Im pretty sure with time I'll be able to fully get into it.The Bad: The soundtrack is kinda dull, for the follow up to a game that had such a rich and memorable score its kind of upsetting we ended up getting generic background music. The intro to the game is very cool with you falling out of the sky and all, but I'm not a fan of how blunt the tutorial section is; in Planescape Torment you wake up on a chopping block, completely unaware of your surroundings, and are then given the opportunity to immediately to go explore and learn about this bizarre world around you; here you end up fuddling around with screens a bit too much.I'll post an updated review when I have one but I'm having fun so far."
