76561198025860351,Recommended,272270,30287556,Posted: 2 March,all,Aenno,"I finished my first playthrough yesterday. I did it in two approaches, without actual pause to anything but a two-hours sleep, and game storyline (including save scumming) takes around 35 hours for me (and it's 23 on game timer). I believe it's means something, at least for me.So, I love a game. My primary complain is that in 4 years you can expect more content. PS:T takes 47 hours (in game-timer, I believe - can't really say) on main+extra completions, and I think I tried to be completionist there, it's 60 hours; but for first Deus Ex, that I take as another Great RPG, it would be 28 hours. I missed at least one merecaster though (couldn't say how to fix it and is it even possible), and I played as social+lore Nano, and it's definitly easiest way.Just in case, I hate current approach to ""remake classical way to gaming"". I've never managed to complete Pillars of Eternity, just dropped... on castle at most. But T:ToN I completed on one approach and not regret a second.Also I should admit, I pleged game on kickstarter 4 years ago, first day I believe (it was, well, 4 years ago, so I'm not sure), and dropped to follow development. I knew about cut features only, well, four days ago, and truth to said I don't mind.So, what's bad for me here.1. Foci. Only three foci, and only one of them is actually fits my game playstyle somehow - I mean that about charisma. I can't say I like it much (I played sage, not charismatic, with Lores, Concentration and Anamnesis maxed), but at least it's better then Breath Shadows or Masters Defence. Also it had nice bonus with Inspired (that works bad for my main character - I believe to get Inspired fettle you must actually ENTER aura, and when you never do it - after your character dies, for example - it just don't renew itself), other bonuses are meh. Putting one more effort to social tasks seems nice, in the beginning, but can't say I recall any moment I needed it. And last tier boni for social focus is ridiculus - when you get that fourth tier, playing around social playstyle, you will supposedly have at least one dot in Persuasion and a lot of Edge to have 100% to social rolls without spending anything. You just won't spend your Int pool to make this ability useful. With actually quite bland abilities foci, I believe, it was possible to put some more. I mean, not as foci was something play-defining for me. I felt more impact from Tides.2. Bugs. Sure, I've take my toll. First, I had scary bug that make every Crisis a chance game - sometimes it just stuck in the middle of somebody action, and only way is quit game by terminate process and replay last save. The worst issue was when it happens in combat with Sorrow in Bloom - it's actually not nice with all that pre-fight cutscenes and dialogs. Also I had a bug with Avina (girl in a quest about five women), when I find her, but didn't rid her from artifact she had, and restored Seria with tidal surge. Well, that was strange, because I don't actually *restored* her, I made her to speak, and she burst in the end; then I entered her fantom, loaded, and voila, Seria was stand there as it should be. Avina spirit never appears, even as quest says I found her.3. Equipment. Well, that's not actual issue, but I really want to have more armor choices.What's bad for other players, but kinda ok for me.1. Companions. Well, there is six characters for selection, and just three slots for them. Normally you'll get Rinn, so it's 2 characters. In that six characters we have one glaive (one-and-half, if you count Aligern), three Jacks (if you include Rinn), and two Nanos. But game definitly build into Int playthrough, not bashing your way, so that's ok at least for me. By the way, official wiki says Callistege is Red+Silver Tide-wise, and that's strange - for me, she is totally Blue. Maybe I don't get Tides at all?.. Anyway, I like Rinn, I like Callistege and I like Erritis. I find them deep and nice, even with ""Callistege personal quest"" I felt blurred from all over the game until last choice in underwater phantom. Hell. Because I felt it blurred.2. Intelligence playstyle. Yes, I definitly can feel how game builded with this way in mind. But, well, Planescape: Torment definitly was build into high Int/Wis character, even if you could play another style. So it's ok for me.3. Rinn. I get it there is a lot of hate about Rinn. Yeah, you would feel yourself as a real♥♥♥♥♥♥when you leave her alone - but, sorry, how do you should feel yourself, getting a homeless girl, protecting her from slavers and then dropping? Yes, that's a♥♥♥♥♥♥move, so it's nice to see that game writing don't let you miss it. Also she actually wasn't useless for me. With high stealth, armed with light shooting weapon and carrying a lot of healing items around, she became a dedicated healer, and then she got Innervate. So until you don't forget to put her in stealth after each cast, she is amazing. Also take in head I don't play with a lot of actual combat.4. Turn-based combat. Actually, that's ok for me. Combat is something that I hated in PoE (with all that timed sword strikes). Tyranny was little better, but still. Hell, I hated that even in Arcanum, and it wasn't something I loved in PS:T.5. Mechanic simplification. Yes, in tabletop game hit points don't exist, and pools used as three types of hits. Actually, in rules it's said that Might pool is ""damage by default"", but neverless. I recalling early betas where there was not dedicated hit points (and interface was HORRIBLE in my option), maybe I'm imagining things, but I even thought ""it's a quite bad idea, because in short game without stable recovery I would save points, as they're my hit points"". Actually I don't like Cypher system, I found it too limited and class-based, but, well... it's nice for CRPG.What's good?1. Setting. Not as much inXile effort, but, I believe, it's nice implementation for Numenera, as Planescape: Torment was nice for Planescape. It actually made me to read Numenera, as PS:T made me to read Planescape.2. System. Well... I feel that it don't realised in full potential. But it's quite nicer that trendy bleak ""generic classical RPG system based on d20"", that seems to be so appearing to modern game design.2. Story. It IS great. Actually I don't believe in ""classical narrative ways"", I believe Mass Effect with video cuts and good (even with all my problems with 1st) graphics model is better for computer game. But in T:ToN I actually read all that text (PoE couldn't get me such way, and every time I starts I played for 2-3 hours only!). I believe it could be great if it was full-sounded and realistic graphics, and more gameplay options but text ones, but story is good enough to suppress gameplay and development limitations. There are things I never saw (Eternal Battle for example), and some things I would make another way or tone, but it is great. And it haven't obvious plot holes I can actually argue, and that's nice again.It's not just interactive book, it'a a game. And it's the best RPG I played for years, maybe sharing the honor with Tyranny first act. Second and third was kinda crap, but first act was great. And T:ToN is fully as good as Tyranny first act."
