76561198030958664,Recommended,272270,30300117,Posted: 3 March,all,cris.f.rocha,"To start with, let me explain that I haven't finish the game yet and that most of my playtime (~50h) came from early access. However I have seen this game evolve since it started early access always, in my opinion, in a positive manner. So far, I already created the character I want to be (having experimented with character creation in early access) and I'm having lots of fun.Pros:Character Creation is different and interesting, keeping you immersed in the world from the beggining. I also think it has a good (short) length when compared with other games that have done similar things (like Oblivion).The game is focused on your character story, not the world's.I loved the choices you make about how to react and what to tell other characters from the beggining (will you lie? or tell the truth and face the consequences).  For the first time in a long history of gaming ( I started playing in the late 80's and yes, I played the original Torment) I found myself interested to see what would happen instead of reloading when things didn't go my way.The use of the stats pool (foci, I think its called) is very interesting. I don't know the rules of Numenera RPG but the way  they are used in this game (like currency) is interesting and different. I found myself sometimes risking the throw of the dice with a 70%/75% to try and save points to a more important choice and (as mencioned before) actually accepting when it fails :)The obvious care in creating the similarities between this game and Planescape Torment: the nameless and, although not amnesiac, totally clueless character; the death mecanic as a feature; the strange world, characters and laws. Planescape Torment is one of my favourite games. In my opinion, this IS a spiritual successor to that game.You can avoid conflict (called Crysis) by choosing another path. You can even try and persuade the other NPC's in the middle of combat, which I found very interesting. Besides that, you can use the enviromnent to your advantage in the fight. As I rather like to avoid fights, all this choices are refreshing.The many ways you can finish a quest. I like quests and feel almost obligated to find every single one and finish it. The amount of ways you can finish the side quests actually begs for another playthrough to find out what would happen if I did it some other way.Cons:I like the graphics. BUT, I agree with some other reviewers that the main character portrait is somewhat ugly (I always play as a female). However, as I said before, I played the original Torment and nobody can call the Nameless One character as pretty :DAnother nitpick is that I miss the other character portraits when talking to someone. I have no problem with reading lots of text but I  like ""seing"" who I am talking to when it comes to dialogs.This game is too serious sometimes. I miss the humour from Planescape (mostly delivered by Morte) that gave a much needed escape from all the drama.I may change my review when I finish the game, but I highly recomend this to anyone that enjoys good writing, a very original and interesting world, interesting characters and a good story."
