,Recommended,272270,31384812,Posted: 26 April,all,Sir Phobos,"The idea of a spiritual successor to PS:T created a ton of hype.Some of this hype was warranted, some of it was not.I didn't follow the Kickstarter campaign and I didn't contribute (I often don't due to past KS dissapointments that I managed to sidestep with my general laziness towards contributing). My perspective comes from not having time to develop ridiculous amounts of hope only to be slapped with disappointment in the end (which is what I've taken away from a bunch of the reviews here).All I know - being a HUGE, HUGE fan of PS:T - is that when T:ToN was announced, I got a warm, fuzzy feeling.With that said, the game ain't perfect. It took 15 hours of slow enjoyment for it to grow on me. That's where I am now, roughly, but instead of coming home from work tonight and going ""Let's see if this gets any better,"" I came home going, ""Let's see how much better it can get from here."" A small shift, but a notable one.On the Writing:I'm the kind of CRPG player that devours lore. I've gotta be in the mood for it, but when I am, I inhale as much of it as possible. I've seen complaints that a lot of the writing in T:ToN was unnecessary and didn't serve the plot... this is true, but I don't see a problem with it. They're building a complex atmosphere that goes far beyond the plot. I have no prior familiarity with the whole Numenera setting, but every paragraph I read, I like it a little more. It's a slow, steady build-up. A large undertaking for a setting with such a massive background. As of right now, the main plot (as it's revealed itself to me so far) is not terribly interesting and frankly feels kinda tropey (""Ooo look at me, son of <POWERFUL♥♥♥♥♥KING/DEITY/ETC> and I'm all confused and have to learn about my powers and my place in the world - blah blah blah""), but it works for what it is. It was way less interesting 12 hours in. More so 9 hours in. Even more so 5 hours in. At hour 3, I was basically calling the game a disappointment. Give it all time to grow on you and try to actually read and visualize the sometimes-long-winded descriptions. Yeah, it's wordy. Yeah, it feels like they went a little too hard after writing, but it's ultimately pretty decent.On the Choice of the Numenera Tabletop System:Again, no background with the setting or the tabletop system but they seriously could've done without it. I absolutely hate the Might/Speed/Intellect stat pool concept. It's kind of cool in certain scenarios, but it feels weak in general. I haven't had any issues with running my stat pools empty before I can safely rest up to regain the points like I've read in some reviews, but stat pools make the game feel a bit more like a chore. Somewhere out there was a more graceful way to handle stuff like this... but that would involve dumping the Numenera system and I guess they married themselves to it.On the Combat:The combat is pretty terrible (hey, just like in PS:T!), but not wholly unenjoyable. It takes a bit of getting used to and there isn't much of it, so I suppose that's a plus. The concept of cyphers is virtually useless. So far I've acquired plenty more than I've been able, or had the need, to use and every time I get a new one, I groan because my main PC gets it and he immediately gets cypher sickness, so I have to figure out who I can give it to avoid the penalties... what's worse is that combat is rare enough that I don't want to put points into cypher-related skills because I'd rather dump them into stuff like Persuasion and Perception to allow me to further dialogue in more interesting ways.On Character Progression:Leveling characters was so-so. In other CRPGs, distributing points and choosing skills was always  something that made the pleasure center in my brain go off everytime my party members flashed on a level up. In T:ToN, it just felt incredibly limited. Starting with only 3 classes and kind of ending up pigeonholed into 4 party members sharing 3 roles, trying to divvy up dialogue-related skills among them while also trying to keep them combat ready with more useful skills feels a bit tedious.On Available Party Members:The size of the cast of party members is pretty standard fare for a CRPG. Party size is 4 (including the main character) and you have a choice of 6 different characters you can use to make up your Last Castoff's team. The characters themselves are interesting in their own ways, but ultimately underwhelming. My current party makeup consists of Aligern, Erritis, and Matkina. Mainly because I wanted to hava decent spread and 2 jacks, a nano with decent combat abilities, and a glaive have been a good mix for me so far (I recently traded Tybir out for Matkina because I liker her backstory more and my Last Castoff is built with Intellect/dialogue checks in mind so Tybir was kind of redundant).Some of the people who have managed to scale this far down this wall of text might be thinking, ""Man, this guy is not making this game seem like it's worth much,"" but I have to say that at this point, T:ToN's whole is actually much greater than the sum of it's parts. At some point, the feeling I was chasing after from PS:T clicked in and I realized that this really IS a spiritual successor to PS:T.For all of it's faults, my initial disappointment turned to disinterest which has now ultimately turned into a simmering appreciation. I'm now hoping that it'll turn at least to a low boil before I see the credits roll.Pesonally, I would have much preferred a PS:T successor that took place in the original game's setting with a much wider scope than just running around Sigil and getting a peek at a a few alternate dimensions. Hell, I would have accepted just another romp through Sigil (the city is constantly changing - they could have done a LOT with that concept, frankly).What we got instead was T:ToN and you know what? I'll take it.-----TL;DRThis♥♥♥♥♥♥ain't your granddaddy's CRPG - Numenera flies in the face of everything you know from D&D-based CRPGs... you'll have to be open-minded and allow for the paradigm shift if you want to actually enjoy it.For PS:T Fans - It's definitely worth playing. The art and general weirdness are actually quite reminiscent of PS:T if you allow yourself to see it. It takes its sweet♥♥♥♥♥time getting good, but eventually you'll start to get those flashes of PS:T that you're looking for. Don't let the completely different setting and system fool you into writing it off immediately.For general CRPG Fans -  If you like dialogue/lore/reading heavy games with incredibly weird settings, you might wanna look T:ToN up and give it an honest spin.For combat-heavy CRPG fans - Move along. Nothing to see here."
