,Recommended,272270,30363871,Posted: 6 March,all,Redhotviking,"If you liked Baldur's Gate, BG2, Planescape: Torment, Fallout 1,2 or Tyranny then you will most likly enjoy this game, It is well written and nailbiting fun, however the combat system and Effort system can be a bit annoying in the start but as you level up and learn more about it, it will infact become quite fun.One flaw in the combat however is the lack of delay turn, especially with aoe abilities that will harm your companions. But this flaw is the only one That bugged me.Another flaw if you will is the lack of re-training your self and your companions so i suggest you focus on reading about the companions and what roles they are suited for and what Edge and pool points you should focus on.My first playthrough had Ali, Mata and Rhin. I myself was a Nano.Ali is easy he works as a close quarter fighter with some spells, making might pool and edge a priority and you wont go wrong, but since he isnt a Glaive his survivability comes from spells and health potion items. But I found him a more likable character than the other melee characters and this is why i kept him around.Mata is another castoff, meaning if she dies in combat he gets back up without any lasting penalties, she is also a rogue with some spell abilities that are very nice. Focus on Speed pool and Edge and you will be fine. Her teleport and damage ability that uses speed is amazing since it only use a move action and places her easily behind opponents and can do untold damage by teleport followed by a weapon strike. Which is why Speed edge and pool is important, she will also aid you greatly with speed releated tasks due to this.Rhin is perhaps the most overpowered companion you can have, but at the same time the weakest by far. She is only a child but her tier 3 ability is amazing and will at this point become a powerhouse of doom. Focusing on Intelligence pool and Edge in the start might crippel you a bit, but in the end game it will pay off. Mainly because her tier 3 ability has 3 uses per day at the cost of 4 intelligence points, the effect is that you do not use up a Cypher. She can also equip a lot of cyphers and this makes her insanly powerful, as a healer and a damage dealer depending on what cyphers you use, but since she is limited to 3 uses per day it is best saved for hard fights. For instance, you have a Cypher you find really early in the game that restores all might, speed and intelligence points you have called the Third man, using this item uses it up, but if rhin activates the ability first she can use it again and again, effectivly being a massive might, speed, intelligence potion that heals all party members near her. Other Cyphers include self ressurect with all pool points restored, aoe heals that heal for a lot and with the proper skills Rhin heals for quite a bit extra, but there are also Cyphers for dealing damage or crowd control and in short, she can infact cause untold damage this way, but only 3 times per day. To make up for her lack of overall health and combat ability a good shield and intelligence based weapon will be needed (or if you divide Speed and intelligence edge/pool evenly she can use dexterity weapon or intelligence weapons) Best to have her at ranged because of her low health points.The story is very well written and with several endings and variations in the epilogue makes it a very replayable game, the main endings can be explored in a single playthrough however, similar to mass effect 3. Door no 1,2,3 (and 4,5,6 in this game)"
