76561198110233422,Recommended,272270,30758414,Posted: 26 March,all,Oddstar,"I recommend this game, because overall I did like it, but there is no escaping the fact that it was a big let-down.  Planescape: Torment was one of my favorite games of all time, so when I learned that it was getting a sort of sequel-in-spirit, made by many of the same people, I was very excited.  Then came the waiting.  I have no information about what was going on behind the scenes, but it seems obvious that there must have been serious development troubles, because this game was announced in March 2013 with a scheduled release date of December 2014, but didn't come out until February 2017.  I started and finished law school, passed the bar exam, and started working at a law firm in that same interval.  If I had not had to wait so long, I would not have been so disappointed.The other problem is that this game is inferior to Planescape: Torment in most respects.  P:T had a more interesting story with more interesting characters.  I really cared about my companions in P:T.  They were traveling with me for a reason.  My companions in T:ToN were just sort of there.  With the exception of Matkina, none of them had particularly good reasons to follow me around.  And none of them, except Rhin, had interesting stories or personal quests.  I also found the main character's story to be much less interesting.  In P:T, TNO had this gripping personal saga, and it was just that: personal.  TNO was confronting his own mortality.  He had to learn from his past mistakes.  In T:ToN, the LCO was just being chased by this poorly thought-out monster for not much reason (once you find out what it is and where it came from, it becomes clear that the Sorrow is little more than a weak imitation of a Mass Effect Reaper).  Again, though, what hurt this game for me was the high expectations I had for it.  I was expecting another experience like P:T, and I didn't get it.Why then, if I was so disappointed, am I giving this game a thumbs-up?  Because it was actually a fairly solid journeyman effort.  As long as you go into it with moderate expectations, this is a reasonably enjoyable game.  Far from greatness, but still decent.  It has an interesting setting and competent storytelling.  It is definitely on the easy side, although there are a few serious challenges.  I had hoped for a lot more, but it's still an enjoyable game."
