76561198052740618,Not Recommended,272270,32886808,Posted: 27 June,all,Glade,"I love the art style, but the game was clearly made on huge budget. Not worth even the half price discount."
76561197983045327,Recommended,272270,30683349,Posted: 23 March,all,Floro,"Just finished the game. Overall impressions are very postive, mostly thanks to the Numenera setting and pretty good writing.The world of the game is pretty bizzare to say the least and in some parts feels like it came straight out from the creepiest pages of some P.K. D i c k novel. Of course while some quests are great, the others are pretty generic, but I wouldn't call any of them dull. The main questline is pretty good too, I found it involving and interesting with all its transhumanistic ideas and moral issues being the highlights. Now that I think about it, the game's plot also has some pretty depressing and would-be shocking moments, but unfurtunetely they are obscured by the overall otherworldliness of the setting.On a bad side, the story is somewhat unevenly paced with the Sagus Cliffs and Bloom parts being intense and content heavy while the middle and the final parts of the game feel mostly like linear fillers or story propellers.Character writing is okay, it's not stellar, but definetely not a failure as many reviewers on Steam suggest. But I must admit I felt the characters to be more of a gateway to understanding the Ninth World rather than some ""very interesting"" personalities you're supposed to run around and pester for the duration of the whole game.Now let's talk about the GAMEPLAY itself. That's where Numenera actually fails in a pretty bad way. While I like the Cypher System and think that it has been implemented pretty well within the game, I can't help but admit that the balance between stat pools is clearly off with Intellect being by far the most superior stat and Might being by far the most inferior, especially considering that the game is short on combat sequences.Another downside is that apart from the game's early stages you never feel threatened to run out of your stats resources, the pools are simply too big and, even more importantly, there's way too much possibilities for resting and refilling those pools. Most of the tasks are also too easy to complete, rendering the whole Effort system almost useless.Cyphers are another interesting part of the game, but just as with the stat pools you rarely feel any need for them because of how easy the game is how rare the fights are.Same goes for the abilities, there's simply too many of them for the absolutely tiny amout of combat within the game. That makes them feel unimpactful and redundant. But that's kind of a problem for the absolute majority of RPGs out there, too much useless and meaningless  junk, especially when it comes to skills and abilities.Tides are a good moral (viewpoint) indicator, but the problem with it again is that they change so slowly that no one decision feel very impactful when it comes to the Tides. It kind of makes sense when you think about it from the ideological point of view, but absolutely fails as a gameplay element.Overall I can recommend this game to anyone who isn't afraid of reading and is looking for an RPG that can offer you more than 10 romance options and 100 craftable items out of 1000 types of resources. It's a rough gem that could benifit a lot from proper play testing and tuning, but even as it is now, it can give you a lot if you bother to read and reflect."
