76561197982844462,Recommended,272270,30243657,Posted: 28 February,all,brassi77,"Okay, this is easy.  This is a traditional crpg following the traditional crpg formula.  All the systems and content crpg fans expect are included.  No system is different enough or lite enough (or too heavy) to be a deal breaker from what I've seen.  It is reading heavy and story heavy as would be expected from a PST inspired game.Fans of traditional formula and content crpgs will like this game unless you really hate TB as the combat and any opposing action is TB mode (called conflict, it is a decent system with decent combat).If you are new to crpgs if you liked Pillars of Eternity, Tyranny, WL2, Divinity: OS, Underrail, I can easily recommend this.  If what draws you to these games is a particular system or subsystem instead of the tried and true and loved traditional crpg formula"
76561198033836833,Recommended,272270,31871370,Posted: 20 May,all,Corrupted Bunny,"This game has done a very good job at being a successor to Planescape: Torment. Looking at it strictly from a Numenera aspect, everything is a little stripped down, but that is to be expected in a video game, but all the core aspects of Numenera are here. The classes, cyphers, artifacts, and the world in general is appropriate for the setting. Your companions are just as diverse as you find in P:T, but it can be tough to find a connection with them unless you really put in the effort. Each has a story to tell if you take the time to find it.Just like the first game, your actions matter. Everything you do and say, every fight you start or stop, will all have a consequence. Your choices will also shape how the world responds to you, for better or worse. Just like the first game, this one is very dialogue heavy, and there are many instances where you can completely avoid a fight if your crafty. My first run took me 16 hours, though I didn't explore every possibility thrown at me, so expect to get 10-40 hours out of this title. With all the diverse options thrown at you, there is some replay value as well if you want to look at the other options availiable. While I took the peaceful path, I didnt really feel like I was missing anything by not going full rambo. This is a true Black Trenchcoat RPG story, so if your expecting you can just hack and slash your way out of every situation and ignore the intrigue and depth of the world, thats your choice, just like every other choice you can make and just like Planescape, find the answer to a very profound question....What does one life matter?"
