,Recommended,272270,30428224,Posted: 10 March,all,ShogunATL,"I remember playing a bit of Planescape:Torment back in the day, but I don't really remember it that well.  So I came at Torment: Tides of Numenera from a fresh perspective, I also know that spiritual successor doesn't mean direct sequel.  So I wasn't expecting one.  I have to say that I was almost immediately immersed in this game.  The Numenera setting is a mind blowing, imagination inspiring setting that I have had such an amazing time in this game.I'm about 30 or so hours in on my first play through, and I really don't want it to come to a close.  I'm also, for the first time in a while, feeling fairly conflicted about which paths to choose, because the consequences of my actions actually seem to carry weight.The combat is simple, but can be challenging as well.  I'm playing a nano, and I've just reached tier 4, so I've got some pretty sweet abilities.  But I actually get more fun out of trying to avoid combat if I can.  My next playthrough will be on a Glaive (the warrior class) and we'll see how differently it plays from that angle.This is quickly becoming one of my favorite cRPGs in recent times, easily eclipsing Tyranny (Tyranny was great, but really really left me wanting more), Pillars of Eternity was good too, but came off a tad generic.  Again, for me, the star of this game really is the setting of the Ninth World, and the ecclectic mix of characters, settings, and abilities you'll find there.  I highly recommend you give this game a try.  Once you make it through the first hour and half or so, you'll be hooked."
