76561197970570259,Recommended,272270,30597990,Posted: 18 March,all,Tanuki Parade,"A fantastically sculpted adventure.  Beautifully drawn landscapes are populated with interesting characters, and the world has a spectacular back-story.  Gameplay itself is fresh, and the story is not combat driven, although the player has many opportunities to engage in violence if it is sought.  Read the first page of the manual, then learn the rest through experience.It's an excellent game in the same vein as Planescape: Torment.  This is definitely worth playing, and inXile should be supported in their efforts to make great rpgs.  In all those millions of words, I didn't find a single typo.---Spoilers follow---The narrative is compelling at first, but falters after the first act, and the game is ultimately over just as my interest peaked.  Maybe I'm a jaded fogey, but I feel like the game needed two more acts, and several more hours of gameplay and interaction in order to bring the narrative to a satisfying close.Overall, the story feels rushed.  Many revelations don't even have time to sink in before the player is forced to make game-ending decisions.  The big, scary antagonist's motives are never fully explained to my satisfaction (they are revealed in a database in a memory-- come on!), and the human antagonist's motivations are ultimately boring.I enjoyed the meres, but felt they needed more impact on long-term gameplay.  I like the memory referencing oolatek and the Heavy Metal movie!!!"
