,Recommended,272270,30661769,Posted: 21 March,all,Xaelvik,"I am one of the exceptions here in that I enjoyed the lengthy dialogue, despite its sometimes tedious verbosity. I enjoyed my experience, although, as other reviewers have mentioned, this game is not without its flaws. Predominantly, I didn't find myself particularly drawn to any party members, as their characterization seemed a bit tepid and lacked that distinctive allure that party members in similar game offerings feature.The conclusion was disappointingly, but expectedly, abrupt. I was pleased, however, that my dominant tides were at least referenced at the end, even if I didn't feel that they had a significant impact. The later sections in the game felt somewhat rushed in comparison to earlier sections.Again, I'll place myself in the minority by stating that the dearth of combat options didn't irk me. Plenty of alternatives exist, new and old, in terms of other RPGs if combat is a must. I enjoyed actually being able to think outside of the box to some extent, even if sometimes the presented options seemed a bit contrived or unimpactful. I really thought the ""Tides"" system, while admittedly simply another version of various RPG attribute systems, was nonetheless interesting in its own right, and characters throughout the game commonly remark on your dominant tides or when you behave in a manner inconsistent with previous choices.This game does take place in a futuristic setting riddled with anachronisms, and it feels like a setting straight out of a Jules Verne or H.G. Wells novel.The soundtrack is pleasant but largely forgettable, and voiceovers are sparse, which is probably a good thing since the quality of the voices, when present, leaves something to be desired.Ultimately, if you're looking for an epic that keeps you on the edge of the seat, I advise you to look elsewhere. This isn't Star Wars or Mass Effect (and I have a great admiration for these), but I can appreciate it for what it is: an enigmatic, intruiguingly bizarre, and beautifully rendered creation with sometimes engaging and sometimes tedious prose that will wholly absorb you if you allow it. It's not going to be in my top five RPGs, but it was an enjoyably unique experience nonetheless."
