76561198027055300,Recommended,272270,29611330,Posted: 31 January,all,MensIuguolo,"YES.So much YES.This game is so good, it's worth every penny. The stories are so rich, character creation is so fluid, it's simply fun fun fun."
,Recommended,272270,30348443,Posted: 5 March,all,The Livid Christ,"Torment:ToN currently holds a score of 84 on Steam, which is why I'm writing this review.That's far too low.The reasons for this title to have a score lower than approx. 92 (which is about what I'd give it) are as follows:Torment:ToN was not designed to appeal to mainstream gamers. It was Kickstarted by people for whom the original Planescape:Torment was one of the best gaming experiences they'd ever had. People buying it on Steam without having had experience with PC games from the 1990s are unlikely to get something they expect.Torment:ToN won't be playable for people who don't read much, or who read slowly, or who need plenty of hand-holding to figure out what to do. It's true the game has a fantastic journal which notes new information for you and keeps track of what you're working on, but players who grew up with the flashing 'X' on their mini-map and an arrow pointing in the direction of the goal are likely to get overwhelmed.Game critics have called the Crisis combat system poor -- I don't understand this, personally. I enjoy the combat system enough to want to see it return in other games. It's streamlined, sensible, and challenging when it should be.Other critics have said the game should have been longer. I'm just out of the first area and I'm already planning my second playthrough. I expect to get many hours of gameplay out of Torment.Note also that this game is not priced at triple-A cost. It's about forty dollars now and I've already got sixty hours of gameplay on it.People say the character models are wonky. I don't understand what people want. I think the graphics are beautiful.In my opinion, the majority of people giving Torment a thumbs-down *must* be the sorts of players for whom it was never intended: children, poor readers, gamers who don't like an intellectual challenge, gamers who depend on iMac-easy tutorials, gamers who need to be told exactly where to go...I think this paints a pretty clear picture.If you love great interactive fiction and the ability to twist your story 1,000 ways, stunningly creative settings, and truly inventive puzzles, this is a game you're going to like.If you're really, really into first-person shooters, you should probably move along.Bravo, InExile. This is easily your best work of art to date.Last note: there are many scorching, damning reviews on T:ToN. Most (all that I've seen) are by players with as few as five or as many as thirty hours in. As I wrote, I have sixty hours and just left the first area. Subtracting a few hours for when I left it paused, let's assume I spent thirty-five hours on that beginning section. What this means is either I'm a terrible reader, or these negative reviewers aren't playing/reading much of the game. Often these bad reviews mention that the game is boring to them. Clearly, if you skim through a book, it's going to be boring. By all means, take bad reviews into account, but note the played hours, too. It's simply not possible to *get* Torment without putting in time."
76561198008137198,Not Recommended,272270,30318169,Posted: 4 March,all,at.stewart,"Enlessly buggy, particuarly combat which often won't let you perform actions. I suggest this be avoided until all the bugs are fixed."
