76561198024168202,Not Recommended,272270,30323595,Posted: 4 March,all,sidΞWay,"Overall...I have to say I'm very disappointed. Numenera is definitely not the game it was promised to be.The Good:Music and sounds - Weird, bizzare and mysterious, just like the 9th World itself.Location design - Incredible, weird, curious, mysterious, ""numenerish"".The Bad:Main Plot - ""What does one life matter?"", in the end the game doesn't really answer that question.Side quests - They are just there, forgettable and in the end it's all about the % roll on persuasion.Linear Structure - There is no open world. Game is divided on hubs, every hub has a few locations to visit, but at one point you'll be asked ""Are you sure you want to continue?"", and then every single quest from that hub will become ""Failed"", there is no going back.Compaions - VERY boring, uninspired, weak compared to the Main Hero, small choice to begin with and the most interesting one (The Toy) was cut out of the final version of the game. They don't have very interesting backgrounds and sometimes simply join you ""just because"". They don't have much to say, and when they finally say something it's not very interesting.Skills and Spells - Not much to choose from, very boring and bare-bones compared to the ""Corebook Numenera"" skills.Turn-based Combat - Sluggish, boring, completely NON-tactical. It was a huge mistake to make a pool on Kickstarter asking if people want turn-based or real-time. It was a bad choice, real-time would be much more tactical and interesting.False-advertisement Polish Dubbing - People were promised to hear the legends of the polish RPG dubbing, and we hear them indeed, for about 3 minutes. And that's it. Read the rest of it.In the end I'd say there are way better cRPGs out there. Numenera sadly feels solid only in some aspects but very weak in the others (more important ones). cRPGs should be all about you, your companions, relationships, friendships and adventures together. About tactical combat and overcoming the odds with clever use of your skills. Dialogues with your companions should make you feel something (like in Baldur's Gate where you could be betrayed in the most important moment as well as fall in love in someone who was near-irredeemable evil and change their heart).5/10, very expensive, very lacking in the core aspects of cRPGs, painfully boring combat, good soundtrack with emotional music but nowhere near as many emotions were put into the dialogues."
76561197979920540,Recommended,272270,30761165,Posted: 26 March,all,Adric,"As someone who's played Planescape: Torment many times over the years, I've been excited about this game since I first heard about it.  In general, I can recommend it on its own terms, and I think that, for the most part, though it does not quite live up to its ancestor's greatness, it does solidly fulfill expectations of existing PS:T fans.Pros:- The degree to which the Ninth World and its denizens are fleshed out and given life is marvelous.  The writing is mostly very good, and occasionally even better than that.  Some of the descriptions manage to find novel ways of conveying impressions and events, which reflects not only on the skill of the writing team but their dedication, in whole or in part, to truly evoking the gameworld.- Several of the companions are highly memorable.  I've only done one playthrough so far, so I haven't been able to fully explore all of the companion interactions (I only used 4 of the 6 extensively).- The visuals are great.  The backgrounds are static and pre-drawn, but the detail, variety and outright strangeness on display bring a heavy dose of the weird to the proceedings.  In many ways, graphics such as these, done right, are more evocative, more creative and more detailed than ultra-realistic, 3D graphics.- Lots of quests, some big, some quite small.  All of them display an attention to detail and self-contained emotional impact that makes them worth completing.  The general story and arc of the game is also compelling and evokes many of the same issues and tropes that made its antecedent so wonderful.- The game system is easy to learn, flexible and, unusually for an RPG, gave me no headaches with regard to the UI or its implementation.- The music is mostly electronic and ambient in nature, but does an excellent job of setting the mood in the various locations in which you find yourself throughout the game.Cons:- I didn't run into a ridiculous amount of bugs, but I did experience crashes every so often; 6 or 7 times if I'm remembering correctly.  All required a forced closure and restart of the game.  Most of the crashes happened only shortly after I'd saved, but a couple happened several minutes into extended combat/crisis situations, resulting in my having to replay a fair bit of dialogue and fighting/evasion afterward.  It's not gamebreaking, but its definitely frustrating.- The game is, as RPS noted, slightly artificial in its feel.  It was definitely designed with a specific audience in mind, and while this can lend a game focus, it also constrains the margins and limits of what the game will or will not be.  PS: T felt organic - Black Isle made the game they wanted to make, and they hoped there would be an audience for it.  This game feels a bit more like a product crafted to meet demand.  As such it doesn't leap out at you with new and fresh insights and experiences the way its predecessor did.- The story while multi-threaded and satisfying, is still essentially about how you try to defeat the menacing bad guy.  This makes it feel a bit more traditional than PS:T.  Likewise, much of the mystery lies in determining the motivations of others, rather than in self-discovery.- Not enough combat.  And before you say, ""But it's not about mindless fights!  And neither was PS:T!"", I'l go ahead and make clear that I know that.  But where PS:T was ~65% story, 35% fighting, T:ToN is, if you avoid unnecessary violence, 85% combat free.  These are rough %, but the point is the same.  I'm glad it focuses on story, interactions, quests, puzzles, etc.  But the game plays this virtue almost to a fault.  I had so many cyphers and awesome weapons and armor, and only got sparing use out of it.  It is possible to play a bloodier playstyle, but it still doesn't seem that it would shift the ratio that dramatically.- Too easy.  Once your main character has enough edge and stat pool boosts, you're basically going to succeed at almost eveyrthing.  Since your companions can also use their stats to help, by the time you're 40% through with the game, or so, barring failure to rest or bring refresh items with you, you're not going to fail many, if any, skill checks.  It's a testament to the story, world and lore that despite this the game remains compelling, but some additional difficulty would have been nice.Conclusion:In a game like this, story and characters are king, so those elements win out over concerns about difficulty and lack of combat.  That said, you can't just ignore the flaws.  There are some things that may turn some folks off and, potentially because it tries so consciously to ape its forebear, it falls short of the greatness of PS:T.  That said, after completing it today, I felt that pang of regret and sadness at knowing the journey was over, the one you feel when you finish a particularly great book or game, and I'm already thinking over when I'll play through it again.  I think T:ToN is a very good to great game that falls short of true excellence, and would recommend it to those who loved PS:T (despite the noted differences), and those who love CRPGs in general, especially if story is of critical importance."
76561198033842478,Recommended,272270,31815496,Posted: 17 May,all,ddrurymd,"I have been playing games on computers when all we had was a monochrome, green monitor and we had to load games with cassette decks. I remember when 8 inch floppies were considered ""high tech"". My first Commodore Amiga back in the 80's made me the envy of every nerd at my school. (""Motorola processor, 512 K RAM, 8 bit sound and  1024 color monitor? Cool!""} Sid Myer's Pirates! on Amiga blew the IBM version out of the water like it was a frigate with 48 cannons. So, obviously, I've played a few games in my life. I have seen technology get better and better and the graphics and sound improve by leaps and bounds.However, I also love to read, especially a compeling story.I guess that is why Planescape: Torment is my favorite game of all time. Fallout 2 is a close second. PS:T  was not the prettiest game at the time. Balder's Gate used the same engine but looked much better.  The combat was clunky in Torment and it was buggy. But the story was original and unlike any RPG I had ever played.  It's like a really good fantasy novel that's interactive. So while reviewing Torment: Tides of Numenera, I cannot help but compare it to what came before it.Torment: Tides of Numenera is a worthy, if flawed, successor. Of course, it's not anywhere close to being as good as PS:T. Is this really a surprise to anyone?  Sequels and spiritual succesors are rarely as good as the original and almost never better. The bar is too high. The story concept for T:ToN is certainly original and the game setting is bizzare enough to rival the Planescape universe. But it seems the developers and writers were too determined to make it a worthy spiritual sequel. The words do not flow natually or organically, the descriptions are, at times, overly verbose and I suspect a thesaurus was used heavily. Sections of it was like reading an long essay from a high school kid trying very hard to impress a literature professor.Other issues:- Side quests in PS:T were interesting even if not related to the main story. Side quests in T:ToN are hit or miss.- The Crisis, used in T:ToN, was tedious and limiting. It could have been better executed with options to include more movement points for actual combat.- The NPC, at least the one's I have interacted with so far, are not particularly compeling. The exception is the child as she  posed an interesting dilemna for a good character. (I'll say no more to avoid spoilers.)  NPC's in PS:T were not only compeling due to their backstories but brought awesomely cool options to combat. (Morte's Skull Avalanche and Falls-from Grace's Lightning Strike come to mind.)On the good side, as I said, the story itself was interesting and gradually unfolded. It was occcasionally predictable but I was genuinely surprised once or twice as well. The different settings for Act 1, 2 , 3 ,etc were well fleshed out, especially the Bloom. (pun intended). And it appears that decisions, or indecisions, in game do matter. That is refreshing.I have played through it once and I intended to play though it again to see how various decisions effect the outcome. To be honest, I did not expect it to be as good as Planescape:Torment but I found it satisfying enough to want to play it again. So that's why, despite the warts, I am recommending T:ToN."
