76561198019695951,Recommended,272270,30547451,Posted: 16 March,all,atemporary*******2,"This is an amazing game in an interesting world.  It's probably the most complete approach to non-combat oriented videogame RPGs.  I'm only listing shortcomings here due to the plane fact that anything I enjoyed about the game couldn't really be improved.That said, it won't be for everyone.  There is quite a bit to read and remember, and while it won't really slow play if you forget something, it seems quite easy to forget enough to render an experience confusing or meaningless.  The game is pretty empty if you don't like reading.  Also, failure is a common tool in the game.  It occasionally provides bonuses and typically gives an alternate solution to a problem.  The shortcomming of failure is that it is random, you can't chose to fail a roll if you think your character wouldn't succeed at something.  So while it offers more freedom of experience by rarely making failure absolute, it doesn't let you wield failure as a narrative option.There are also a few places where gameplay isn't smooth.  You can't always click certain objects that are clickable which leads to your characters moving over the object and, since your characters are clickable for some reason, they end up getting interacted with.  It would probably be a good idea to move most follower interactions to the character portrait rather than the game window.  Also, the flourish on creature names takes up a large amount of the game play window often obscuring the creature names when you click tab to show all interactable objects.  Maybe there's a way to shrink them that I don't know about.A minor quibble I have is with the hard follower limit.  While it's fair that certain party members want nothing to do with one another, it seems that restricting the party size to 4 encourages a player to often swap characters in the middle of stories to ensure that they don't miss anything.  It would make much more sense to include all available characters as desired.  You also end up cycling through unused characters to get at their resources during contests, this creates a weird dynamic that doesn't play very smoothly.  I would expect some better method of accessing the other character's insights and abilities without swapping through characters regularly.One weird narrative issue I've come across is the primacy of intellect.  Maybe my personal bias is manifesting as an in game bias, but it seems solving things through intellect is always a more rewarding path, particularly in a game where lore is the reward for many interactions.  Beyond that though, you will occasionally be faced with social interactions that could be solved with violence, that never present violence as an option.  I realize that this is the norm for RPGs but choosing a more peaceful path when there isn't an alternative makes that choice less meaningful."
