,Recommended,272270,30440954,Posted: 10 March,all,Joker,"Hello friends this is my somewhat short, but hopefully somewhat useful review of tides of numenera. I'm going to break this review down into four separate categories followed by my closing thoughts.-----------------GraphicsSo let me be honest with you this games graphics isn't anything special, It's a crpg and I feel graphics isn't one of the major factors you should judge this genre of game on. That being said character models weren't all that impressive but they weren't by any stretch terrible. Some world environments actually looked pretty interesting and had a beautiful tone to it. I feel like the special effects of this game was its strong point in the graphics department but also it's most frustrating part.For instance there are certain parts of the game when you meet the sorrow and witness its grandstand this is amazing looking and creates a moment of awe, as well as some other maps you encounter look incredibly vibrant and colorful. While others look very plain and unimaginative. The most frustrating part is getting special passives later on in the game. These passives create a colorful shine effect around your character, near end game my guy looked like a walking Christmas tree about to give me a seizure.Overall the graphics where solid and did its job well that job being able to support the story and help tell it.Graphics : 7/10-----------------SoundSo let me start of by saying the soundtrack in this game was good mixed with a feeling of who gives an S***. There were times where the sound matched the mood correctly and gave me a sense of emotion and feeling to the task or event at hand. There was also times where I didn't even notice the music in the background at all tuning it out. Which made me wonder how their soundtrack was so hit and miss I could never really wrap my head around it. I feel like the major points of the story the music fit in well supporting the mood while delivering the message it set out to send us.All the music in between I honesty couldn't care less. None of the music was really terrible just most of it didn't really matter to the game. I feel the sound track aside all the ambient sound and voice acting (what little there actually is of it) is superb and immersed me more into the game.Sound: 7/10-----------------GameplaySo there is a common theme in my review which I'm sure you all have noticed. That theme being the story is the major strength of this game and I'm judging the other aspects of it based on how they support or elevate the story. Which brings me to my next category game play. Oh boy this game is hit and miss there are amazing moments to be had followed by head scratches and for game play this also holds true. The game play is honestly not very imaginative in this game and extremely straight forward.There are two aspects to the game, running around talking to people and making decisions based of stats, skills and tidal abilities, then there's the combat. The first part is fun and has rewarding moments along with emotion and enlightenment. Though I feel that this ties more into the story with a mix of it being game play. The game play being you holding tab looking for things to interact with and get into the lore and story of the world. Which leads me to the second part of the game play which is more of the definition of the word and that's the combat.Man oh man, I honestly don't know how to describe the combat for you I feel like the combat almost had no purpose. I mean it's not real time which that's okay but it's a turn based system without any real strategy or relevance. Abilities really didn't matter at least for me they didn't I was a glaive did not upgrade any abilities or used any at all for the entirety of the game. I put points into edge, stats pool, and effort I believe that's what it was called. Then I proceeded to click and auto attack on every enemy I went against till they died. Ciphers once again cool concept, it's a really powerful item that gives you stat boost or damages your foes or both but it can only be used once before its lost.Unfortunately I used a cipher one time against one enemy throughout the entire game, even then I didn't have to I just was curious to see how they work. In the end all I did was stack artifacts that made me hit harder and sell all my ciphers I had for gear. Maybe this is a glaive thing and the other classes aren't so fortunate but by mid game my guy couldn't die and my auto attacks where taking 50 to 75% of enemies life pools a strike. To me I feel like the purpose of combat was to make the game last longer and nothing more, that's how bland and tedious it was for me as a glaive at least.Gameplay: 7/10 (the aspects relative to the story, the combat id give a 4/10)-----------------StoryLast but not least by any stretch, the reason why I bought this game and I'm sure many others did the story.Tides of numenera is carried by its excellent story telling, lore and connection you feel with the castoff and his allies. If by any chance you are 1/3 into the game and aren't feeling the story I advise you to stop playing the game. Why? because that's how much this game relies on its story to flourish. Without it, it's not even worth a steam summer sell for 75% off. Is the story perfect? No, but is it interesting fun and keeps you waiting for what happens next? Hell yes. *Slight spoilers* you are a cast off of a deity called the changing god who is in essence immortal. He achieves his immortality through transferring his consciousness from being to being improving himself from his previous life. Your role is one of these castoffs trying to figure out what is going on in this world.The game has a lot of choice leading to numerous altercations and outcomes depending on how you act and treat your followers or the world around you. The voice acting is amazing but there is barely any which is unfortunate because I believe if the game had more of it, it would appeal to a larger audience. Warning if you do not like to read do not purchase this game it's basically a visual novel with combat being its mini game in between chapters. Overall this game is good but it has its share of flaws that are out shined by its interactive and amazing story telling. I would love to tell you more but I do not wish to spoil the main reason why you should play this game.Story: 9/10Closing statementsI had fun with tides of numenera I believe the game could have been a lot better though, There were a few moments in this game that where the best I have ever played in a crpg. That being said it was also inconsistent at times which lead to frustration, the combat is poor and needs to be revamped for future games. Also, some story telling which was the best and most brilliant in the game were flashbacks. To be able to play these flashbacks in real time would have been awesome instead we got a screen that we click on with nothing to show for it. Overall in the end I had a blast it was well worth the 26 hours I spent to complete it.Overall: 8/10"
,Recommended,272270,30271906,Posted: 1 March,all,Mike,"Torment: Tides of Numernera is a unique, enjoyable RPG experience and a step up in storytelling, lore and creative quest design from previous crowdfunded CRPG efforts such as Wasteland 2 and Pillars of Eternity. The same traits that made Planescape Torment such an unforgettable experience are in full force here- bizarre worlds to explore that ride the line between sci fi and fantasy, difficult moral choices, and and the ability to persuade/manipulate your way out of practically every confronation in the game. Without spoiling too much of the story, your character- the Last Castoff- is a relic of a mad shapeshifting immortal who also has the ability to seemingly cheat death time and time again. The Castoff goes on a long quest to piece together their memory while discovering their role in a grand scheme that could shape the fate of the worlds forever.Much of the player's interaction with the world comes through the stat system, which is simplified in a way that is both clever and functional. Alll of your character's abilities are reduced to into three stat pools- Might, Speed and Intellect. These act as as resources that can be used in both combat and practically every conversation/quest interaction option where a typical RPG might require a charisma/dexterity checks. The only way to recover these stat pools without using items is by resting, which typically costs a good chunk of money and eats up valuable time (which directly impacts certain quests). What this means is that the player needs to ration out these stats carefully, forcing players to consider other creative ways to solve problems if their party's stats look tight. While these stat checks being odds based does tend to encourage save scumming I feel like this isn't much of an issue because the game tends to give interesting results forfailingas well as succeeding in them.One example of the care and detail that went into Torment is with the Heretic's Fork, an obscure, expensive piece of equipment that takes up a valuable artifact slot and comes with no useful combat bonuses, but grants you the ability to ""scan the surface thoughts of most people or creatures you speak with"". Just to see what would happen, I bought this item and stuck it on my protagonist for the rest of the game, and was pleasantly surprised to find that all of my companions and practically every NPC I met from that point on had unique dialogue lines of dialogue (some of which directly influenced conversations). This is a lot of effort for one seemingly gimmicky item that the majority of players will probably never use.Combat is simple to learn but tricky to master, and there is plenty of room to creative clever character builds in the three unique classes and the variety of obtainable items. My personal protagonist was a Light Armor/Weapons using Jack with a focus on building up a massive Speed stat, raising her Evasion to such a high degree by the end of the game that she was effectively immune to all basic weapon attacks. Cyphers are monstrously powerful consumable items which you can purchase and find throughout the game, and intelligent use of them can allow you to overcome overwhelming odds even with a character build not focused on combat. Fettles such as flanking and spells which buff multiple characters encourage intelligent positioning and teamwork. I often found myself deliberately taking the violent path to resolve quests towards the end of the game, simply because I enjoyed seeing all the abilities and powerful gear I was collecting go to good use.The major complaint I see from some other Steam Reviews is that either combat is too difficult, or that enemies tend to mob and kill off the main character before you even have a chance to react. While enemies do tend to focus fire on targets- you know, like any compentent AI enemies should- the Stealth mechanic greatly increases the survivability of your members, and getting quality armor and artifacts helps your characters survive some pretty serious beatings. I am convinced that these players either are unable or unwilling to build effective characters or try to hoard/sell all of their Cyphers instead of using them in combat.If there's any legitimate issues to be had with Torment, it would be with the length of the game- even if you complete all the sidequests you're likely to finish in around 25 hours. The game comes rolling to a seemingly abrupt end and you don't have a chance to revisit any of the past locations you've been to to see more of the consequences of your actions. Another small issue I had was that the conclusion for Erritis's storyline was pretty weak for otherwise very likable companion. Also, the game hypes you up the entirety of the story for a big final boss fight against the giant eldritch abomination terrorizing your mindspace, but this simply never happens no matter what story path you pick, which is a bit of a letdown.These flaws do little to diminish what's so great about to what the game offers as a whole- a spectacularly original and detailed world to explore filled with interesting lore and memorable characters. Torment kept me hooked from start to finish with its compelling story, rich writing, and difficult storyline choices. I would definitely recommend it to anyone who played through Pillars of Eternity or the old Infinity Engine games, as well as any CRPG fans in general."
76561197987492734,Recommended,272270,30346059,Posted: 5 March,all,rVn>,A great cRPG and a worthy successor to Planescape:TormentAvoid if you don't like a ton reading :-)
76561198006569366,Recommended,272270,34824021,Posted: 8 September,all,Barbarryian,"A rather difficult game to rate.I've played 3 of inXile games (wasteland 2, pillars of eternity, and this), and they all have a somewhat limited audience, due to their somewhat dated structure and heavy amount of reading.And I will say that I think tides is my least favorite game I've played from them.The good:  The setting is like nothing I've seen before, and is easily its strongest component.  Far, FAR, future, where anything is possible.  Very original set pieces, characters, puzzles, etc.  It took a couple hours for me to get really invested in the story, but it's a pretty great one, all in all.The bad:  Combat is pretty dull.  Found that auto-attacking pretty much did the trick the entire game through.Some of the exposition can get a bit longwinded, even more so than pillars at times.In general, this is almost an interactive book.  The combat challenge is almost non-existent.  And that's ok!  It's an interesting and original story.  The lack of challenge is striking from that of pillars, which I had to turn down to baby mode.However, I think my biggest problem is that it's ~$45, and I was stunned that I finished it in about 15 hours.  And that's after chasing down every side quest I could find.  Plus, I only found 4 party members, which seemed low.  It felt like I was just getting into the story and then END.Anyways, I feel that its gameplay to dollar value is quite low, especially compared to other inXile games.  If you're a fan of the setting, and of reading, it's a decent buy.  If you like InXile games, it's much the same, just surprisingly short.  In either case, I'd recommend waiting for sale (I did).But if you're new to inXile or 90s isometric RPGs, I'd easily recommend wasteland 2 over this."
,Recommended,272270,32221448,Posted: 6 June,all,u1345m,So strange and interesting book.*9
76561197973330377,Recommended,272270,30891427,Posted: 1 April,all,BannerDay,"First off, this is one of the only games that I have played recently that I have been motivated to complete.It's a fantastic game that should be experienced slowly and thoroughly. The writing is the standout feature - it's easily some of the most engaging and imaginative I've seen in a game. Most of your playtime will be spent reading. Plenty of choice with clear consequences.Constructing/defining your character (your character’s CHARATER, not just your stats) is central to the game, which is unfortunately refreshing given the current state of roleplaying games.Combat system is solid, but it's possible to avoid most fights if that's how you want to roleplay.Your companions are interesting, and you will become invested in them if you give them the time. Although, I do think that each character could use one more quest to strengthen the investment. Experience is not gained by characters outside your party, so you are encouraged to choose three and stick with them.Overall, if you are willing to invest in the game, like you would with a good novel, it offers a very rewarding experience."
