76561198103290668,Recommended,272270,31074302,Posted: 11 April,all,jgjsmith006,"It's not often I feel compelled to write up a review of a game but some games such as Torment: Tides of Numenera deserve it, partly because of quality but also because of the anticipation of waiting so many years for it to be released.  I was a massive fan of the original Planescape game  (which at the time was underrated by a number of prominent gaming magazines), and is my favourite RPG of all time.  With regards to Tides of Numenera I feel that it has the potential to be nearly as good as the original Planescape but falls someway short.  That does not mean that it is a bad game, only that it is a good game that has a number of flaws that prevent greatness.First the good:Setting - originally I was disappointed that the Planescape campaign was not being used but having seen the decline of Dungeons & Dragons over the past couple of decades (which Planescape is a part of) in the end I was glad that they went with the Numenera campaign setting.   As a reader of Jack Vance and a fan of the blend of sci-fi/fantasy that influences Numenera, I found the Ninth World instantly engrossing, and, just like with Planescape, felt I wanted to explore it further.  I particularly enjoyed the less linear sections of the game including Sagus Cliffs and the incredible Bloom, one of the best game worlds ever.Story/characters - I enjoyed the story, which kept me engrossed towards the end of the game, and appreciate the amount of text used to flesh it out, which I believe was over 1.2 million lines of dialogue.  I enjoyed in particular the back-story of the world's inhabitants and the games subplots perhaps more than the main story itself, and felt that this area started to approach that of Planescape.   Some people were complaining about the amount of reading involved so this game is not for everyone but for myself I thought it was well written, comparable with Planescape.  I also liked that you could basically complete the game with almost no battles if you chose to, relying on other skills such as guile or stealth.  Other reviews were not happy with the lack of spoken dialogue.  Whether this lack of dialogue was a design choice or because they ran out of money I am not sure, but I do personally find spoken dialogue too slow and distracting and much prefer reading at my own speed.   In term of characters they were generally very interesting and I felt that the personalities of the companions that accompany you were well thought out and each one intrigued me, particularly Rhin.  The downside to characters was that there were not enough of them but I will bring this up later on.Loading screens - when I heard this game used the same engine as Pillars of Eternity I was immediately apprehensive as my experience of that game had been ruined by loading screens.  Thankfully, Torment load screens were not a problem on my computer and the game was structured so there were not dozens of rooms to be entered (probably because of the game engine).Stats/Skills - I found the use of Might, Speed and Intelligence an interesting system and how you could put points into tasks.  I particularly liked how failing a task could actually open up new options in the game world, which offers potential new playthroughs.   I also enjoyed the types of skills on offer and levelling up characters, although I felt the level cap was a little low (see not so good).Combat - there were a few complaints about the turn-based combat (which Planescape did not use unless you count pressing the spacebar to pause the action) but I have to say that I am a fan of this as it allows me time to think and strategise.  I thought Tides had much better combat than Tryanny (which seemed to be mostly AI and confused the hell out of me), but not as good as Divinity which had some very interesting spell combinations.Now the not so good:Length - this for me was the biggest weaknesses, partly due because of the games strengths.  Around 40 hours into the game, and really starting to enjoy myself, all of a sudden I found myself levelled up to tier 4, and the game was starting to draw to a close.  40 hours seems reasonable but this was after completing every quest and having already played a large section of the game with a different character type before restarting, so it is feasible you could complete the game in much less time. I feel that the world setting was so good, particularly the Bloom, that I just wanted more, and it was very disappointing that it suddenly nosedived to a conclusion.  From what I am reading online it appears that the developers cut a whole game world and it certainly feels so from the flow.  You really feel that you are building up to something fantastic only for the carpet to be pulled from your feet as you are steered towards the end.  Hopefully, they can allay some of these issues by releasing additional downloadable content.Transition Linearity/Maps - although there are a couple of hub areas which give a degree of choice of how to approach quests there were a couple of linearity issues with the game.  For example, once you complete a certain stage you cannot go back.  There are a couple of points I would have liked the option to return to Sagus Cliffs to see if choices I had made elsewhere have influenced events in the city but this never happened.  This is possibly linked to the length of the game but there was a point on one map where it looks like you had a choice of portals to different locations but in the end you are shuttled through due to the approach of the Sorrow, which I found a little disappointing.  I also felt that more dungeon areas should have been introduced, particularly during the Valley of the Dead Heroes level which is more a sequence of rooms.Tiers (levelling up) - this is related to the shortness of the game.  The maximum tiers you can reach is 4 (which is about 16 levels) and when I levelled up and could go no further, I had the sinking feeling that the game was starting to end.  Ideally, I would have liked a bigger game world and the opportunity to reach tier 5 - downloadable content please!Bugs - there were a number of bugs in the game that I noticed including one that actually prevented me from taking a certain action to complete a quest resulting in the game freezing.  I also encountered a couple of freezes during battles.  With so much time spent developing the game this is something they should have got right.  Thankfully, unlike certain Atari RPGs (Greyhawk - which when patched is fantastic btw) at least they did not hinder my enjoyment of the game.Merecaster Sections - I grew up on Fighting Fantasy gamebooks so I am not put up with interactive text but I found these sections incredibly dull.  The problem was that they contained massive amounts of text and I was not clear what (if any) effects my choices were having.  I will have another run through the game to see if this improves.Minor gripes:Extras - while not a major issue I would have liked some form of overall world map to have been available.  Planescape also had a codex/bestiary which I found interesting and I feel that Numenera missed out on this, although there may be some plans to introduce this via updates/downloads.Overall I would say this is a good game that just misses out on great due to missing one major game location which leaves it feeling slightly unfinished.  I think expectations hindered it, and the fact I was not a Kickstarter Backer mean I am not as disappointed as I could have been, but it is worth purchasing if you are not put off by reading and turn based combat.  The characters, story and gameplay options mean that it is interesting enough for a second run through using different character companions and the Bloom is one of the great game locations of all time.  I would definitely be interested in more updates and games involving the Numenera game setting."
