76561198007312077,Recommended,272270,30619007,Posted: 19 March,all,pitfiend,"My feelings toward Torment: Tides of Numenera are mixed. While much love and dedication was obviously put into this CRPG, its hard to ignore it's weak points.I chose to recommend this game because at the moment of writing the game's overall score deserves some positive correction upward. I think people should be encouraged to play this game, and games like this in general (such as PoE and Tyranny), though when it comes to this title they would be served best by curbing their expectations.Pros:* A fascinating world full of wonders to explore and discover.* Interesting questlines and characters, for the most part.* Well written narrative, for the most part.Cons:* An incredibly frustrating combat system with long waiting time between rounds. (Although you can choose to avoid combat most of the time).* Banal and unsatisfying asnwers to some of the game's most intriguing mysteries.* Rushed ending that fails to meet the expectations.Verdict: Play this game to enjoy the ride and don't expect a mind blowing closure, just try to avoid the combat."
,Recommended,272270,30627709,Posted: 19 March,all,RickelodeonTV,"Torment is a more than worthy successor to Planescape:Torment, evoking the vast feel of colossal worlds and impacts with your every word. Every companion has a well-thought-out reason for being, and I was amazed at how some of my choices came back around. Was the whole point of everything as personally earth-shattering as PS:T? No. Nothing ever will be. Accept this, and let the Tides take you as close to that apex as we'll ever get again."
76561198139846465,Recommended,272270,30628396,Posted: 19 March,all,strekalalex84,"I would recommend this game but with some reservations. It might be best to get the game when the price drops or after future patches and added/re-added content. I enjoyed playing the game, with three different playthroughs, but not without some criticism. The very nature of this being hyped up as a spiritual sucessor to Planescape: Torment already set expectations too high and caused them to over-promise, which ended up coming back to bite them. But taken for what it is, it is a decent game. It just could have been more.World/Story - The setting is imaginative and intrigueing and the story is pretty good. The plot is a bit linear and, unfortunately, it feels a little rushed in the 2nd half of the game. Relative to my expectations for an RPG, the game's playtime is dissapointingly short and the areas are small. You get a strong sense that they had earlier iterations that were much more epic and had twice as many locations, but they ended up cutting out half of it. That's probably the biggest dissapointment for me. It's all over too quickly.Character Progression - On a related note, the level cap comes a little too quickly, at least if you play as a completionist and do all side quests. This is a feel bad thing in any RPG. In all three of my playthroughs, my main character reached the cap with about 1/4 of the game left. There was 1600+ experience past that which I couldn't use. That's easily enough XP for another 2 Tiers. If they added abilities for 2 more tiers, they could easily raise the cap to 7.Choice and Consequence - This is probably one of the aspects that they nailed pretty good. There are usually at least 2 or 3 ways to resolve most quests, sometimes with vastly different results. There are also lots of variable dialogue options that affect your tides. That said, in the long term plot, there isn't as much of a sense that your choices matter as there could be. It's all sort of foisted upon you as you're rushed to the ending.Graphics/Art/Music - The area backgrounds look beautiful and are well done. The character/NPC avatars are much more simplistic and clunky in comparison. The background music is pretty good for setting atmosphere, though maybe a bit empty at some points. You do get a sense sometimes that there was extra graphical/animation polish that existed in earlier iterations that they took out. This aspect is not that big of a deal to me though.Dialogue - It should be expected for this type of game that there is a lot of dialogue. This isn't a bad thing in and of itself. Anyone who wants a hack and slash dungeon crawl doesn't get what a game like this is supposed to be about. That said, sometimes they got overly verbose for details that didn't matter. 90% of the game is reading text and it could have been paced out better with a little more combat and exploration. Even Planescape: Torment wasn't as heavy on the text-adventure aspect as this is.Combat - Combat isn't quite as bad as some people are saying. It isn't a great though and the Crisis system can get buggy. With the relatively few combat encounters there are, and the fact that you can talk your way out of most of them, players may feel like they rarely get to use their combat abilities and thus character progression feels a bit empty. Much the same goes for all of the Cyphers, which are unique one-time use items, but you don't get enough of a chance to actually use them.Skill System - The general idea of the skill system is pretty good. The way they implimented it, however, probably makes the game a bit too easy. With investment in Intellect based skills, Edge points, plus the ability to use your companions to help with skills, it is easy to pretty quickly get to a point where skill checks are no longer a challenge. With a few exceptions, after the beginning it's possible to breeze through most of the game's skill checks regardless of your character build. Needs to be rebalanced with more risk and limitation.Tides - This is one of the most interesting and flavorful aspects of the game. The way that your choices determine your tides and the world subtly reacts is pretty well done. My one complaint about the tides is that I wish there were more explicit ways you can use them in gameplay. With a few exceptions, the tides are just a display of the morality of your actions and are not as reactive as they sold it to be, within a given playthrough. The subtle effects of the tides do show more across multiple playthroughs though.Companions/NPCs - Aside from Rhin and maybe Castillege, the companions don't feel as fleshed out as they could be. There is a significant lack of companion interaction, party banter, and voice acting in general. The game also pretty much encourages you to choose a team in the first area and stick with it, and there's no going back to the first area once you leave. There are no mid or late game companions. The lack of NPC portraits also takes away from immersion. Also, unlike Planescape: Torment, most non-quest-related NPCs can't truly be interacted with, they just show one liners above their head if you click them.Basically, I think the game has a lot of cool ideas and potential, but they just didn't flesh it out as much as they could have, or they gutted their own ideas a little too much to a point where quite a few features that were either promised or that actually existed in earlier iterations of the game ended up being left out entirely (including: NPC portraits, more voice acting, more companions, two or three more game areas that could have easily added 10-20 more hours of content, and so on). That makes the game feel a little empty or over streamlined.With all of that criticism, I still would recommend the game because it is still a unique experience, it has a unique setting and story, and it has its share of flavor. In some basic ways, they did capture the feel of Torment, they just could have refined it more instead of putting time and money into making it a console port and over streamlining content. I also am holding out hope that there will be future patches and add-ons that make up for at least some of the criticism."
