76561197978867242,Recommended,272270,30418309,Posted: 9 March,all,MilesMk1,"I had relatively low expecations for this game, and was very pleasantly surprised. I was hoping for an rpg/adventure where exploration and dialogue counted far more than grinding away at combat, and that's what I got along with a solid story, fun setting, great writing, and entertaining companions.Did inXile hit it out of the park? Well, if you compare it to the original PST, then obviously, they did not. The game is smaller, occasionally frustratingly so, and not nearly as ambitious. (although one of the upsides of the relatively small size is that there's virtually no filler) But that's an absurdly high bar. Compared to other indie(ish) RPGs like PoE, Wasteland 2, Shadowrun Returns, AoD or Tyranny, it's difficult to not call Torment: Tides of Numenara an excellent game. (unless the whole ""lots of talk and hardly any combat"" concept is not to your taste)Actually, speaking of other similar titles... I think it's absurd and unfair that this game is currently far worse reviewed than, for example, a game like Tyranny - which had a lot of potential, but was clearly released unfinished, and features far too much pointless filler. I think many of the poor reviews are less about objective judgement and more about shattered, impossibly high hopes."
76561198123938072,Recommended,272270,30432875,Posted: 10 March,all,latvanypekseg,"I just finished this game and enjoyed it pretty much. It is a successor of Planescape: Torment in a way that it is an exploratory game. T:TON is about discovering the denizens of the sixth world, finding clever solutions to people's problems, using junk you found on the way to invent new solutions. It is fantastic, the quests are well thought-out, the game truly shines in this aspect, every quest has several solutions, you can find another one and another one way to get what you want. You can see the amount of love and care that was sunk into this game and it really makes a difference.To add to this the designers managed to solve a problem as old as crpgs: How to avoid ruining the whole experience by saving/restoring. It is pretty hard to die, yet characters have three pools which they can use to solve different tasks which refresh every time they sleep. If you sleep a lot, you can solve every problem that can arise, with a little twist: Some quests change when you sleep, some goals become unattainable as time passes. This system is brilliant and most likely will become a new basic mechanic for crpgs.The world itself is beautiful and exciting, however I feel it is a bit fragmented, some cohesion would have made it even better. Several companions can be hired, most of them are interesting, and have rich backstories. The story of the game is enjoyable, not as great as P:T's but still entertaining and iimmersive.Considering everything I can only recommend this game to everyone."
