76561197991430581,Recommended,272270,33664096,Posted: 19 July,all,kbabij,"Perhaps the biggest flaw of this game is the inevitable comparison to Planescape: Torment.  This is obviously an intentional comparison on the part of the designers, and you can see some elements that are the same in both games: an amnesiac main character that can't stay dead, an unfamiliar alien world, belief shaping reality, a mysterious force hunting the main character, etc.  The truth is that if this game hadn't invited the comparison to Planescape: Torment, it would still likely be judged the same way.This game stands on its own, with some flaws detracting from the otherwise good quality.  I had originally started playing this game on a PS4 console, and quickly abandoned that experience as it was clear that the experience was intended for PC even if console releases were simultaneous.  I found the story to be compelling, the dialogue to be fresh and interesting, and the sheer artwork to be awe-inspiring.  The more I play, the more I get drawn into the rich world which they have created from the ground up.The few flaws that exist with this game mostly have to do with mechanics relating to combat and the points system.  Rather than opting for a system inherent in the Baldur's Gate series and Planescape: Torment in which the characters will continue to attack, cast spells, etc. until you choose a different action for them, this game is entirely turn based.  This means that you have to choose each and every action for your characters each and every time, from movement to special abilities to attacking the same monsters.  Although this system is inherent in games such as XCOM, Wasteland 2, and others, it somehow feels out of place in this type of game, especially since its predecessor Planescape: Torment did not feature a turn-only system.  And although the points system each character features allows you to increase your chance to hit with a weapon or to use a special ability in combat, these points are used so frequently that you will find yourself working hard to replenish them simply to get an edge from battle to battle.  Add to the fact that these same points are used outside of combat in scripted encounters to activate certain abilities, and you understand some of the frustration inherent with such a system.  And if you choose to rest to replenish these points rather than use inventory items to replenish them, the game actually advances certain quests and story elements independently.  This makes resting a tricky proposition if you're trying to solve certain quests that may advance without you.But even with these flaws, that's not enough to make me dislike this game.  It's too interesting, too beautiful, too engrossing to put it away and dismiss it.  It's not Planescape: Torment, and it will never be.  But on its own, it is a solid game worth the time of anyone who plays and enjoys  similar games, especially games that give you such a rich world with surprises around every corner."
