76561198019584864,Recommended,272270,33736918,Posted: 22 July,all,Devorlast,"Good game, lots of negativity from folks who kickstarted it thinking it would be something different.Combat is weird but if you play the game focusing on diplomacy and smarts you can avoid almost all encounters in the game. I think I had to fight maybe a total of five times in the 40+ hours it took me to finish the game.The story is interesting and fun to follow. Plenty of side quests and LOTS of flavor text everywhere.Items and their descriptions are almost an art form all on their own. Even things that are seemingly ""vendor trash"" have rich, interesting descriptions and sometimes can be used in weird ways. I don't think i have had this much fun reading item descriptions since Baldurs Gate 1.Biggest flaws in the game are the linear progress in each ""act"" and the very abrupt ending of the game.There are no marked ""acts"" or chapters in the game but there are about four distinct location hubs, with the fourth one being the end game one that is pretty much linear. The districts are interesting and pretty large but still seem pretty locked tight compared to even Baldurs Gate series.The final of the game comes out of nowhere, you are literary doing some questing and following the story and BAM final mission comes up. Depending on your choices in game and how well you did in certain ""mares"" the options at the end of the game will change but ultimately it doesn't feel as fun as the ending of even Planescape. And of course your in game choices will be described along with their consequences at the end in a series of static text blocks... Well, at least its better then the initial Mass Effect 3 ending.Overall its a good game, well worth the price tag, takes over 40 hours which include probably about 10 hours of reading if not more. If you are set on fighting everything in your path and would like to take the force solution to your in game problems then you should get some other game, combat 