,Recommended,272270,34215276,Posted: 13 August,all,Sorenzo,"So far, it lives up to its name.Which is very, very good.I was kinda worried when I realized it was a sci-fi game, but they've really captured the essence of Planescape: Torment, despite the setting being so... new. Frankly, apart from a few things that are rather too outlandish, I'm very impressed with the setting. It's not easy to create a compelling setting without relying on previously-known elements, but they've pulled it off.I wouldn't necessarily recommend playing this game and Planescape: Torment back-to-back. I think much of the beauty of Numenera happens when something is vaguely reminiscent of something you saw long ago... especially since that fits the theme of the game so well. But I guess I can't tell you to go back in time 20 years just so you can play through Planescape: Torment and then forget most of it.But I can recommend you buy both games, play Planescape: Torment now, and then play Numenera some time later. ;)Edit: If you like a game with a lot of combat in it, you're going to have to be willing to be a jerk to the NPC's. Don't play diplomatically. ;)"
,Recommended,272270,30318801,Posted: 4 March,all,Hawke,"Summary.Torment: Tides of Numenerais a party-RPG, 35-40 hour long, the battle system is poor, the story is fine. The game is good, but it fails to compete with either nostalgia or the other RPGs available. Approaching it without comparison or expectations would provide the best experience.Update.Extra content has been added for free in the latest patch (1.1.0).Update.Completed the 2nd playthrough.The game tracks most of player's choices, but doesn't show if an event is the consequence of player's actions, time-dependant or a default scenario;There is not enough information in battles shown (i.e. no log, no rolls, no opponent's stats);There is usually one weapon per type (Heavy, Medium, Light) per stat (Might, Speed, Intellect) per area (except for Medium Speed weapons, there are sometimes 2 per area).Key points:The story is fine, the lore is rather bizarre, the information is presented in pieces to form the whole picture by the end (some side quests bite later during the main ones);Several ways to resolve quests;The decisions sometimes provide immediate or clear results, due to the game's structure you see some outcomes only in the epilogue;Areas changesubtlydepending on the actions taken;Terminology is different for the sake of being different - ""nano"" is a mage, ""CRISIS"" is combat, ""fettle"" is an effect/status, ""oddity"" is useless loot and ""numenera"" is an artifact in the most common meaning (matearial product of human culture/civilization);3 battles in the firsrt 15 hours, more unskippable battles later, turn-based combat, hard to say how balanced it is;No stealth outside of combat, which means inability to scout areas before encounters or start combat with an attack from stealth;RNG-based skill checks in dialogues encourage to use F5/F9 often;Several choose-your-adventure (text-based) sequences, several dialogue pazzles (i.e. answers mean something);Good graphics, good animations (but there's no option to speed it up);""Heavy"" UI, no option to sort items in the inventory (which gets more problematic as the player acquires more items);Good soundtrack, annoyingly voiced commands (turned off VA after 10 hours);Customizable controls;No fast-travel and a lot of running through the same locations;Some side quests are bugged (v.1.0.1);Companions, who are available, but not in the active party, don't gain experience;Tides seem to be the same thing as allignment in D&D and it can be min-max'ed as well.There are other games doing what TToN is trying to do, but better.For hardcore RPG experience -The Age of Decadance;For nostalgia -Pillars of Eternity."
