76561198029006705,Recommended,272270,33418142,Posted: 9 July,all,Aegrum,"I wanted to avoid comparisons to planescape: torment but since tides of numenera is selling itself as a thematic successor (which it succeeds at), some things need to be talked about.Like Planescape, Tides is a cerebral text-heavy game where you can talk yourself out of most combat situations or avoid them all together. If you build a strong combative character, you can find yourself fighting quite a bit. But no matter how aggressive you play, the fighting will be dwarfed by the amount of reading you'll be doing. While the combat is solid and has a nice feel to it, this is hardly the best game for strategic turn-based combat. What you should be coming to this game for is the engrossing world and story, it's unique cast of characters, and the special mood this game offers.Both games feature a protagonist unsure of their identity who is faced with philosophical and existential situations in highly imaginative bizarre/alien worlds. Both deal with similar themes but remain different enough to branch into separate areas. ""What can change the nature of a man?"" is at the heart of Planescape, and ""What does one life matter?"" is at the heart of Tides.If you have played Planescape, I feel it's important to go into this one with limited expectations to be pleasantly surprised at all the similar feelings and nods to planescape rather than looking for what does or doesn't measure up. I think the mixed reviews are partly do to that, and also from people buying the game expecting something like Pillars of Eternity, where combat plays a much larger role and is significantly less text-heavy.Despite PS and Tides being in different universes, you'll recognize some names and items and even some of the areas+characters will remind you of those in planescape - again being different but resminicent. Tides takes place in the numenera table top world which itself is largely influenced by the planescape D&D campaign setting.There are some mechanics I really enjoyed in this game - such as failing skill checks can often lead to interesting variations in the quests, and may open up new doors that you otherwise wouldn't get to. In a few negative reviews I saw people saying that they wish they could do this or that not knowing that they totally could if they had made different choices previously. inXile's previous game Wasteland 2 offered an incredible amount of ways to navigate situations and complete quests, and Tides continues the possiblities by adding depth to skill check success/failureOverall, this game offered a great 40 hour ride with future replayability. I'll continue thinking about it. Highly recommended!"
