76561198003343758,Recommended,272270,30460823,Posted: 11 March,all,Grimourum,"So far Torment seems like a very well written story driven game that makes me feel like I am playing a highly immersive choose your own adventure book. It creates a world that is very unique and interesting while fostering mystery and intrigue. It seems to take the role-playing part of being an RPG to the next level while including some cool mechanics to give it a twist. Having options to resolve an encounter instead of just mowing down the baddies is very interesting. If you want something different from the traditional RPG, this could be a good pickup."
76561198039983702,Recommended,272270,30439914,Posted: 10 March,all,wendigo211,"I vacillated on whether to recommend this game or not.  It is not as good as Planescape: Torment, but as long you temper your expectations, it is an enjoyable experience.  However, it is somewhat overpriced right now.  I would wait until it is on sale for 20-30 USD before buying it.The setting very much is that carnival of weirdness and peculiarity that one would expect from a successor to Planescape: Torment.  The Numenera setting is one of people trying to survive in the ashes of previous highly advanced civilizations; civilizations who built devices that appear magical to the explorers of this strange world.  This allows for devices that flagrantly taunt the laws of physics without the need for a sci-fi explanation as no one is alive who understands this technology.  While Numenera uses technology to recreate the setting that D&D used magic to simulate.  It lacks some of the coherence of the Planescape setting.  Within Sigil, belief had the power to alter reality and anything could be a doorway to another plane of existence, under those guidelines everything made sense.  There are fewer rules governing the Numenera setting.The main plot passable but flawed.  You are the castoff of a human who has gained immortality by jumping from body to body through history.  Whenever he leaves a body a new personality inhabits that castoff body with some of the memories of the original.   This person is being chased by an immortal monster, and that monster is also chasing all the castoffs.  This monster is pursuing you because of something called the tides.  The problem is the tides (and the problem with the tides) are never well explained.  You essentially start the game being told you must repair a device that will stop this monster, and all your efforts in the game resolve around finding someone who can repair this device.  You never really question why you are doing all of this, beyond basic survival, until the last 10 minutes of the game.  Note that all the endings of the game are determined by your choices in final conversation.The gameplay is not very good.  Much like Planescape: Torment, Tides of Numenera does allow you to talk your way through quests instead of fighting.  The problem is, while conversations are arguably the focus of the game.  They are not the main gameplay mechanic.  The gameplay is really focused on crises that can be resolved using stealth or combat.  Most of the crises consist of more than just beating the enemy and the early crises can be fun to play. As you progress the character mechanics and acquisition of items reduce the crises to trivialities.  The game features a very generous system of stat pools that can be used to purchase successes.  It is so generous that it trivializes the game.  Any conflict you encounter can be solved either using the consumables you acquired or spending some points from the pools that refresh whenever you rest.  The pools offer larger bonuses than skill levels, making skill choices redundant.  This also limits the character variety and reduces replayability.Despite these flaws, there is joy to be had in exploring the world in this video game.  Some of the side quests are well done and the descriptions of the items and locations are interesting and entertaining.  The game clocks in at a respectable 20-30 hours, not great for an RPG you probably will not be replaying, but it is a memorable experience."
