76561198026764468,Recommended,272270,30259688,Posted: 1 March,all,Nyarly,"Hello all,I am early in the game and from what I could see, the game is good, but not good at the same time.I am really hesitating between recommanding and not recommanding the game at the same time.First, the game is gorgeous, you can't say they didn't make a great work there, the pillars of eternity engine is certainly great (though I would have liked some coop like baldur's gate).Then the story, the story is certainly worth it, it is really well written, intriguing and you really want to go deeper into it.The narrative is certainly the strongest point of the game with some stuff I could argue about like the change of scenery coming out of nowhere which in game is only a story, you take a couple minute to get into and by the time you're into it, you're back in reality... Some game effects could have been added to make more immersion.Music and narration goes along with it, all pleasant and makes you want to hear more.The the mechanics, the gameplay, the combat system... Well, let's start by saying that turn based combat isn't bad, I personnaly like turn based when it is well made such as fallout 1,2 or more recently divinity original sin!BUT WHY OH WHY CHANGING THE MECHANICS SO MUCH??? The first torment was a blast combat wise... This one is really a deception... They threw away the D&D mechanics relative to the Torment universe to create a really poor system with 3 stats (might, speed and intellect) which form a ""pool"" from which you can drain points to perform successful actions or having a chance to fail them... Meaning, if you make a warrior, you will have high might and most likely succeed your might test all the time until your might goes down to 0 ! (example if you have 9 in might, you make an action and decide to spend 3 points to succeed it, you will have 6 left in might until you can replenish it)The system is horribly bad, just like the cyphers which are kind of like a one time use magic object.Going away from the classic D&D rule set is the biggest mistake they made, they should have conserved it even if it would cost more to have the right to use them!Which also did cost them the class system which is down to the nano (the mage/mechanic), the jack (jack of all trade, master of none, kind of rogue) and the warrior, well, what's more to say about it? Master of weapons and armors.Heck, even taking the pillars of eternity system would have been better! It was their engine so why not take their combat system instead of this horrible pool system!Even by beeing a warrior with everything in might, if you empty your pool, you can fail a test... Same with the nano I am playing with right now.Finally, the interface is really blend and I would have appreciated to see the portrait of NPC you're talking to avoid confusion while reading a dialog between more than 2 characters because this ask you to be really attentive to each name popping during a conversation.The dialog window could have been made better to avoid the need to scroll down when making a choice.Appart from that, the game, the animations of the decor, the story, everything is great and is the reason why I would recommend the brilliant writing of the scenario... Don't play Tides of Numenera hoping to get a deep RPG system... The RPG is all about the story and what it will make you discover althought many already state the story feels short.Fort a 50$ game, this is quite a let down! I am finally glad I didn't back the game.The world while seeming quite alien is lacking of mystical creatures and npc like the modrone, the black knight, morte, Anna, Ignis... And all the fun, weird, original and deep characters which could travel alongside with you in the original game. They made us go back to something classic."
76561198035796040,Recommended,272270,30592830,Posted: 18 March,all,jacobcrafoord,"Having played Planescape: Torment many times, and with all the information I had about Torment: Tides of Numenera prior to the game released, I had the highest expectations when I bought this.Although not as great as Planescape: Torment I still think it's a good game with a good story. One of the main differences is the main character, the last castoff, that - unlike Planescape: Torment - isn't the main focus of the story and is more of a tool/vessel whom the story unfold around. The game is more 'a' journey than 'my' journey. The roleplaying game is toned down and the emphasis is on the narrative.The companions, with a few exceptions, feels less likable and interesting compared to those in Planescape: Torment. I wish the developers had dared to go further with their imagination in the creating process.Very nice graphics. I loved it. Sagus Cliff, the Bloom...beautiful, fascinating. Characters, for example the last castoff, is unfortunately quite ""robotic"" and the visual effects of spells/effects on characters a bit annoying after a while.Music is great, especially in the beginning - ambient - though there were an overall lack of songs that stood out, like ""Fortress of Regrets"" in Planescape: Torment. Sound effects are sometimes too prominent.Many of the quests and sidequests are even better than those in Planescape: Torment. Lots of different ways to solve them with lots of different results.New system for skills, abilities and fighting. I like it and I think it's promising. The biggest problem is that it's too easy. In the beginning of the game it's ok but quickly the challenge disappears. You fail a skillcheck because you choose to (can sometimes give interesting results), not because you run out of skillpoints.8/10Knowing what I know now, do I regret buying it at full price? No.Will I buy any expansion in the future? Yes."
76561198027930252,Recommended,272270,29744503,Posted: 6 February,all,Darion,"I finished the first act in the current beta and I wanted to share my thoughts with the community. Now I am a long time favorite of games like Baldurs Gate and Icewind Dale + pretty much all other RPG's, but I never played Planescape Torment - unfortunately, so I was excited to try this alleged successor to what many claim to be the best RPG of all time.First of, this game is different in the sense that it is a true rpg - meaning that you can actually avoid combat pretty much all together through diplomacy, threats and deception. Now to some, I imagine that might feel boring, but to me its really a treat to be entertained in an old-school kind of way. It feels like you are living in an excellent book, where your choices matter. Its also sci-fi fantasy, so don't expect to find much in terms of familiarity in neither the world itself or its inhabitants. Sure there are a few kinks here and there - but nothing gamebreaking, however the lack of character customization seems disappointing.I would recommend this game to people who enjoyed a game like Pillars of Eternity for its writing - not the combat. You absolutely have to enjoy lots and lots of complex reading, so if you are a 'big words hurt my brain' kind of person, then you will probably not like this game at all. There are no fancy coup de grace killcam animations and the actual combat feels underwhelming, but I like to think of it this way; I may find the♥♥♥♥♥of a baboon ugly, but I still like to watch it sway in the brisk wind ...Rating: 4/5"
76561197970320868,Recommended,272270,33737654,Posted: 22 July,all,sizer99,"This is a game for people who want to read a lot, and find wonder in books like A Wrinkle in Time, Mister Bass, or Golden Compass.   There are so many great ideas here, just spread out for you then thrown away, entire series just flashed on your retinas then discarded.If you're here for a balanced RPG or combat, just forget it.   This is not your thing - this is an RPG that attempts to recreate a creative human GM spilling his guts with creativity, and your wonder and a frission down your spine at what this means for your lovingly created and curated character.  By the end of the game you'll be OP, but who cares?  It's the journey that matters.  You have the all the options here, there has never been more choice in an RPG.The question is whether wading through piles of color text is a pleasure or a burden for you.  For me it's a pleasure, so I'm enjoying the hell out of it after a slow start.  But if you don't like, seriously LIKE reading, you'll miss the point and give it a 7/10 like most reviewers who've been trained for Shooty McFace."
