,Recommended,272270,31985151,Posted: 26 May,all,Pan,"As a successor to Planescape: Torment, TToN is naturally narrative and dialogue oriented. This is not limited to conversations, but permeates to the game's combat and mechanics. There are times when, after combat initiates, you will be able to use your actions to speak with enemies instead of attacking. You may also use these actions to hack into a machine and disable enemies. It is worth noting that you will be reading during most of your playtime, in the spirit of PT and other old school cRPGs. If this is not your thing, stay away from TToN. If it is, you are in for a treat.I found the writing to be beautiful and the narrative fulfilling. Being a spiritual successor to PT, a lot of the themes will be familiar to people who played the original, as well to elements in the game's structure and its narrative. It is a very personal story and delves into interesting philosophical questions similar PT's.While PT's combat was good at all due to its focus on narrative, I found TToN's combat to be competent and enjoyable though not its strongest suit. Nevertheless, the strongest point in combat was that you could ultimately avoid it or end it through dialogue or, in some cases, stealth.The actions you make in combat require you to spend points from a pool based on your character's skills, but these points are not limited to combat, but can also be used to succeed on tasks during dialog and other interactions. I found this to be a good way of bringing together all of these mechanics and allowing you to choose which is more important.I dare say that Torment: Tides of Numenera is a worthy successor of Planescape: Torment and builds upon the main pillars that made the original so beloved. A recent update added a new companion character, which means I will have to play it again, and I will gladly do so."
