76561198032524950,Recommended,272270,30646155,Posted: 20 March,all,Theo,"MAN.  I don't write many reviews, but I already feel compelled to share my thoughts on this game.I'm roughly 1.5 hours in and I'm in love.The story is alredy compelling.  I'm traversing every conversational path I can with the worry that I'm negatively effecting my relationship with the strange and fascinating characters I've met already.  I can't wait to read more about this world.The user interface is GORGEOUS.  It's fast, sleek and polished.  It's flowy and vibrant and relaxing. Very well done.The character creation process was definitely my favorite done in any RPG I've played to date.  And I've played a LOT of them.  70% of my library is RPGs.  I love RPG's.  So much.The music is to die for.  It's beautifuly done and it changes flawlessly as tensions change in dialogue.  I already feel like I could play this entire game with VERY little (and quite possibly none at all) actual combat.  And I LOVE it that I have that option.  I'm already envisioning replays with different attitudes and builds in mind.  I believe they will create completely unique experiences already.The price?  Meh, so far I'm feeling good about the purchase.  But I think to make that detrminaiton before 20 hours is probably silly and something that would have to be changed later.  So I'm abstaining on this topic while leaning towardy the thumbs up side in the early leg of the race.If you've been watching this one, get it.  If you start to watch it now, pounce the INSTANT you see it go on sale.Games this well done take me back to my 15 year old summer nights reading choose your own adventure books while my actual imagination was still vivid.  Now I'm old and jaded and I require advanced technology to take me there.  But this game is doing an EXCELLENT job so far."
76561197970585835,Recommended,272270,30799058,Posted: 28 March,all,Hexaflex,"T: ToN is a great game and a worthy successor to the Torment name. The strengths and flaws of the two games are pretty similar, so if you're looking for an immersive, story (text) heavy game to explore and think your way through, here it is.+ The world and characters within it are fantastic, it's easy to immerse yourself in a place that feels alien setting-wise but familiar mechanics-wise. This is the thing I love most that both Torment games share.+ The writing and quests are overall very good. The quests react pleasingly to the different ways you can solve them and the descriptions and dialogue are often thought-provoking and fun. There are times when a little too much text is dumped on screen without much other interaction, but if you don't enjoy reading you wouldn't be playing a writing-heavy RPG in the first place. People who are complaining about ""reading a book""... what the hell did you expect?~ The combat is solid, but not wonderful. I did run into a couple of bugs in combat (I didn't encounter any outside of it) which was annoying, but eh. I expect a few bugs in a game this size. I actually enjoyed the turn-based combat here more than the Real-Time-with-Pause of Pillars of Eternity, which surprised me a bit, being a big oldschool IE fan (BG, BG2 etc).- It's quite easy. The combat and skill checks are at least reasonably challenging to begin with if you avoid sleeping while you do all the first town quests like I did, but after that there's not anything that took more than an attempt or two to ace. I don't really play narrative games for a heavy skill test though, I play for the story and setting. Making the moral and investigative choices in dialogue is where the ""difficulty"" lies in my mind.- Yes, the final act ends a bit abruptly and the game is a little shorter than I'd like, but it's not worth getting bent out of shape about. 64 hours for a methodical runthrough of an RPG seems decent enough to me. I don't care what budget the game had or where that came from, I care if the game is fun and (in my mind) worth the money, and this one is.If you're the sort of person who likes investigating all the nooks of a game before moving on, this one has plenty of fun to discover. People wanting a more mechanics-heavy challenge or who get bored reading long chains of dialogue, then yeah, stay away."
