76561198089954745,Recommended,272270,30458762,Posted: 11 March,all,Amlin,"TLDR: If you like crpgs or want to try and dip your toe into the genre, this is a good place to start.  There isn't too much combat to worry about and slow your enjoyment of the story.  Great replayability, if you like reading and want something different from typical scifi or fantasy play this game you won't be disappointed.As a gamer that has never played the original Planescape: Torment and having limited experience with crpgs, I went into this a little intimidated.  The ones I've played were daunting in terms of gameplay, while they were all rich with deep storytelling the pacing of the game would often be hampered with the endless amount of creatures which  you would have to fight between story sections.  Some of which could be a frustrating wall until you grind even more weaker monsters to progress yourself.That is not the case with Torment: Tides of Numenera.  I completed the game on my first playthrough in 40 hours, throughout that time I had very limited combat encounters and instead got to enjoy and immerse myself with the well written story and side lore that each environment you cross paths with uninterrupted by needless combat.  The developers weren't kidding when they say they have a books worth of story packed into this game.I enjoyed this game, on the second playthrough you'll likely skip a few dialogue here and there but not in the same manner as other rpg games where you'll make a few different choices but be lead the same way.  In this game, there's a lot of replayability.  There is no way you can see everything in a single playthrough even if you save-scum."
76561198065922938,Recommended,272270,30463305,Posted: 11 March,all,gomfedj,"I remember playing Planescape torment years ago, liked the way combat was not the center of the game, was very different at the time and took me awhile to get used too. This game feels very similar in that aspect, combat is an option, but often the 3rd or 4th or 5th, not the 1st option. There are only a handful of required fights (i believe required, otherwise my choices may of forced them) even those often can be run away from, or assited by using objects on the battlefield to change things.I overall had a great time playing this game, even if i did save scum a lot, just to see the different outcomes at times of success or failure. I feel like unless you do that,  or play the game multiple times you will miss a ton of the dialog/lore/backstory/etc...Not sure if the game is worth the 45$ price tag, but it is SURE better than a 60$ price tag and i know i had more fun with the game than some i spent 60$ on! I say give the first hour or 2 a try and see if you like it, otherwise there is always the refund option."
76561198068961460,Recommended,272270,30463639,Posted: 11 March,all,anubis.hellraider,"Overall a good game but nowhere close to the original ""Plancescape: Torment"".The game desipite it´s only roughly 30-40 hours long campaign still a good match for the original in aspects of general playtrough (focus on story not on battles) and unfortunatly companions (P:T as combat aid, T:ToN as combat aids (minor) and skill mules (major). Aside from that they are glorified NPC´s)The new mechanics work and fit into the story.The overall story is also good (if short)Despite the overall matches sofar there is however one, or rather three, big part/s that invalides the game as a successor instead of a standalone: It has nothing to do with the charactes, places or story of the first game.Places:As the name of the original suggest it takes place on the ""Planes"" more specificly the first 2/3 take place in Sigil, a place called the City of Gates (to other planes) and is filled with creatures of said planes. T:ToN on the other hands play on the ""ninth world"" and among other things you see at least 2 spaceships and in ""flashback"" one space station.Characters:The only character that comes from the first game is Adahn. First Game he was a fictional character that could be brought to some sort of live by telling people that it´s your name. T:TON makes it the name of the previous host of our body in the game.Story:The only elements of the original story that makes it into this one is that the Protagonist can´t die (with exceptions). The reasons in P:T was that we underwent a ritual to seperrate us from our mortality. The reason in T:ToN is that we were made this way as a vessel for the changing god.Summary: Would buy again (even the Immortal Edition but that one only in a Steam Sale) but take down the ""Successor of Planescape: Torment"" Award. That one is undeserved. Even as a ""spiritual successor""."
