,Recommended,272270,31229868,Posted: 18 April,all,Z. Bilious Todd,"This game is full of amazing ideas and insane concepts, all packed into a condensed space. Though you probably know by now, only play this if you really are in the mood to read!It's one of those things that throws so much overlapping content at you that you'll feel overwhelmed until you realize you only really have to pay attention to the stuff that interests you (ala William Gibson or Cloud Atlas). The game emulates the world it creates: everything feels old (it is really retro) and confusing; like layers upon layers of unknown culture, you are often lost, but find ways of sorting out the problems by exploring.Gameplay wise, you mostly LISTEN in this game: talk to NPCs, learn about the world, solve quests. The combat is fine thanks to it being turn-based. Inventory management is minimal, as are most systems not related to dialogue (though it can be odd that, when you level up, you are often making precise decisions about things you will never use in the game at all). The ""pools"" system, like RPG stats that deplete based on checks that determine if you fail or succede, is novel.It's telling that many people's favorite part of of this game are what's called ""meres."" Essentially when the game strips everything else away and become a simple choose-your-own-adventure. At its heart, this game is a graphical representation of a very inventive paper & pencil RPG sourcebook, which a cool story running through it.Also: If you are a fan at all of Jack Vance, you should definitely pick this up!"
