76561197989776377,Recommended,272270,30513911,Posted: 14 March,all,Dunhart,"I wasn't a kickstarter and though I've been looking forward to this game as someone who loved Planescape: Torment, I subjected myself to as little hype or foreknowledge as possible.THE SETTING: It's a bit like a cross between Fallout and Planescape. The premise of a Sci-Fi/Fantasy world filled with gadgets that might do something cool or blow your face off is very appealing and could possibly lend itself to all sorts of great stories. Absolutely loved it, I hope they'll make more games that use it in the future.GAMEPLAY: I really like the Crisis system and the idea that you can, and indeed sometimes have to, resolve them without combat. In fact, I experienced so little combat I can't even properly comment on it.STORY: WARNING, SLIGHT SPOILERS. This is where the game lets itself down a bit for me. Of course, I still compare it to Planescape: Torment (which I rate as the best video game of all time, storywise), so it's still not BAD. Just, could be better.I liked the party characters, none of them felt flat or one-dimensional (with the exception of Erritis but perhaps that was intentional). I just wish game developers stopped enforcing arbitrary headcount limits.The foreshadowing you can get with Anamnesis gets a bit spoiler-y at times; I guessed several major plot twists (like the importance of the Ghostly Woman) before I even left the first city.The abrupt ending feels more than a bit rushed and the central question ""What does one life matter?"" gets a bit flimsy at times, where Planescape: Torment's ""What can change the nature of a man?"" never dropped out of focus.Also the final end sequence I hated, for the same reasons I hated Mass Effect 3's ending. Throughout the game, the primary antagonist (The Sorrow) is represented as a hateful force that tries to kill you through no fault of your own and cannot be reasoned with. At the last moment it basically goes ""Turns out trying to kill was really hard, maybe I should just talk to you instead"" and offers the same insane troll logic the Reapers in ME3 used as justification for trying to kill you. And then the game forces you to agree to play along with the Sorrow's one-sided offers for compromise; The only ending where you don't is shown to be a bad one."
