76561197993432458,Recommended,272270,20884544,"Posted: 31 January, 2016",all,mattminus,"*Updated After Full Release* - As, I'd hoped, the complaints below have been addressed. This game is a worthy purchase if you're a fan of Planescape Torment or Numenera________________________________________________________________________Let me start by saying that I hope I'm able to change this review someday. I love Numenera,  I loved the original Torment, and the small parts of this game that work show a lot of promise.That said, the ""game"" is far too incomplete to get a recommendation at this time. It's at a very early alpha level of bugginess, such that all but the most patient of gamers will not be able to tolerate it. If you don't imagine yourself happily persevering after the fourth time you've crashed during character creation, you should probably wait a while before checking this game out.Even if you are prepared to save after every action and reload a lot, brace yourself for a shocking lack of content. You'll get a quest, head out for the dungeon, and then get a dialog telling you to imagine you just completed the quest. At the current state of development, the game is very thin.These two complaints should be addressed as development progresses. One thing that won't change is that this game looks and plays like a game from 1999. Thats not a bad thing, it's just what a gamer like me wants, but it's not for everyone.Those complaints aside, I haven't returned it and continue to slog through it. Why? Because it's a great portrayal of the Numenera setting and system. Because the writing is top quality and the dialog trees are extensive. Because I suspect that I will love this game when it's done and don't want to wait for them to finish it.So, if you're the kind of person who loves Planescape and plays in a weekly tabletop Numenera game, this title is worth a look. Otherwise, I'd keep my eye on the forums and pick it up when it's got a little more meat on it's bones."
76561198072317318,Not Recommended,272270,32400385,Posted: 13 June,all,HappyHead,"It IS a good game, but I just couldnt bring myself to like it.The real issue for me is that the question, ""what does one life matter"", asks nothing of those who hear it beyond its answer. It is a ""mere"" philosophical question. As one of the developers pointed out, the game repeatedly hits you with this question from a variety of different and intetresting angles, but the question dies once it has an answer and, unfortunately, may people already have somthing of an answer walking in. Players are simply actualizing what they already believe into the game world rather than being challenged by it.In Planescape, the question was ""what does it take to change the nature of a man?"" From the beginning the question was deeply personal in nature because it's basically saying ""there is somthing wrong within you, how can you change that?"" When Planescape hits you with the question from a multitude of angles, you are drawn into the suffering of the characters and identify with their struggles WHATEVER it may be because all of their struggles are deeply human (being born to a certain family, being wracked with guilt, being unable to do good like you want, being consumed with ones own trauma, ir simply being unable to rid yourself of the darker aspects of yourself. etc etc etc.)I guess that's why I can't really recommend the game. It IS a good game, but I went into it expecting to find the same level of humanity its predecessor had and was left wanting. Numenera asked me who I was but Planescape asked me how I could change. For this reason, there is no moment from Numenera that has stuck with me, but Planescape? That game has stuck with me and has captured my imagination for years.If you have yet to really answer the question this game asks, MAYBE this game is for you. Maybe somthing in it will stick with you and change you in some way. But I for one just can't shake the feeling that Numenera took one step forward in game mechanics to take two steps back in impact."
